INSERT INTO `algorithms` VALUES (1,'bearssl','BearSSL\n','Thomas Pornin','C','0.6.3','18-02-2025','MIT',1,'https://bearssl.org/',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','BearSSL is a compact and lightweight cryptographic library designed for use in resource-constrained environments such as microcontrollers, embedded systems, and Internet of Things (IoT) devices. It provides essential cryptographic primitives and supports a subset of SSL/TLS protocols, focusing on minimal memory usage and portability across different platforms. BearSSL\'s architecture is built for simplicity, reducing the risk of implementation errors, and it comes with a self-contained build system that does not rely on external dependencies, making it easy to integrate into small-scale and embedded projects. Its design philosophy is to offer just enough functionality to enable encrypted communication and data protection, while remaining efficient for devices with limited computational and storage resources.','BearSSL\'s primary limitation is its restricted support for modern cryptographic algorithms and TLS protocol extensions, as it intentionally omits many advanced and legacy features to keep the library small and maintainable. It does not include support for all the latest TLS versions or extensions, lacks integration with hardware security modules (HSMs), and may not be suitable for large-scale enterprise deployments or systems that require compliance with strict security standards such as FIPS or Common Criteria. Additionally, BearSSL\'s smaller developer community can result in less frequent updates and slower response to new vulnerabilities compared to larger projects, and the lack of comprehensive features may limit its adoption in applications needing more robust or versatile cryptographic functionality.','[{\"command\": \"git clone https://www.bearssl.org/git/BearSSL\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/lf66suztfeq1fhkpe5cji/bearssl1.png?rlkey=b96yga2vadix3uxf4y7spakki&st=r3plgets&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the BearSSL project from its official website using Git. It creates a folder with all the project files.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd BearSSL\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/fomquollz2nyet2dwn1ns/bearssl2.png?rlkey=0z86s6shtzn6y3f2sn9zzteko&st=zopmzbyw&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves you into the `BearSSL` folder. You can now access and work with its files.\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/5xyafinpnz20i2j3cjuqx/bearssl3.png?rlkey=c0bbspwil830lyniipg9zf6x8&st=hhca35zy&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the BearSSL project using the default settings. It builds all the necessary files from the source code.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <string.h>\\n#include \\\"bearssl.h\\\"\\n\\nint main() {\\n    // Input data to hash\\n    const char *input = \\\"Hello, BearSSL!\\\";\\n    size_t input_len = strlen(input);\\n    \\n    // SHA-256 output (32 bytes)\\n    unsigned char hash[32];\\n    \\n    // Initialize the hash context\\n    br_sha256_context ctx;\\n    br_sha256_init(&ctx);\\n    \\n    // Process the input data\\n    br_sha256_update(&ctx, input, input_len);\\n    \\n    // Get the hash output\\n    br_sha256_out(&ctx, hash);\\n    \\n    // Print the hash\\n    printf(\\\"Input: %s\\\\n\\\", input);\\n    printf(\\\"SHA-256: \\\");\\n    for (size_t i = 0; i < sizeof(hash); i++) {\\n        printf(\\\"%02x\\\", hash[i]);\\n    }\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n    \\n    return 0;\\n}\", \"explanation\": \"To compile the program, use these two commands:\\n`gcc -I./inc -c bearssl_test.c -o bearssl_test.o`\\nand then\\n`gcc -o bearssl_test bearssl_test.o build/libbearssl.a`.\\n\\nThe first command compiles the `bearssl_test.c` source file into an object file using the headers from the `inc` folder. The second command links the object file with the BearSSL library (`libbearssl.a`) to create the final executable called `bearssl_test`. After that, you can run the program by typing `./bearssl_test` in the terminal. This will start the program and let you see how BearSSL works in action.\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/pmgyhbvcqf1toq40rpkap/bearssltesting.png?rlkey=1cvz6r1mkfz0iegqg0eoasn83&st=dq8k9sot&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The image shows a terminal output demonstrating the use of BearSSL to compute a SHA-256 cryptographic hash.  \\nIt takes the input message *\\\"Hello, BearSSL!\\\"* and generates its corresponding 64-character hexadecimal digest.  \\nThis test confirms that BearSSL is correctly implementing the SHA-256 algorithm for secure hashing.  \\nBearSSL is a lightweight cryptography library, often used in embedded systems or resource-constrained environments.  \\nThis example highlights the library\'s ability to provide robust cryptographic functionality efficiently.\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(2,'boringssl','BoringSSL','Google','C/C++','0.20260508.0','13-04-2026','Open Source (ISC-Style)',1,'https://github.com/google/boringssl',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','BoringSSL is a cryptographic library maintained by Google as a fork of OpenSSL, with the goal of providing a secure, reliable, and easily maintainable cryptographic backend for Google’s own products such as Chrome, Android, and various server-side services. It streamlines the codebase by removing deprecated and unused features, simplifying the API, and introducing additional safety checks and security improvements. BoringSSL benefits from continuous internal and external review, modern development practices, and is tailored for high-performance and high-availability production environments. It is widely tested at scale in production traffic, and its design decisions are guided by the needs of large-scale cloud and browser deployments.','Despite its strengths, BoringSSL is not intended for third-party or general-purpose use outside Google’s ecosystem. The API is not stable and can change without notice, making it unsuitable for projects that require long-term support or backward compatibility. Unlike OpenSSL or LibreSSL, BoringSSL does not guarantee a stable API/ABI, does not accept feature requests from the community, and discourages external adoption. The documentation is primarily aimed at Google engineers, which can make integration and troubleshooting difficult for outside users. Its focus on Google’s needs means that some features, extensions, or algorithms present in OpenSSL may be missing, limiting the library’s suitability for use cases beyond those anticipated by Google.','[{\"command\": \"sudo apt update\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/a31vhc14kejmvm0efyocu/boring0.png?rlkey=if3k533vrxyqii5wd7v99q048&st=89i9079b&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command updates the list of available packages from all sources. It helps ensure you get the latest versions when installing software.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo apt install git cmake ninja-build clang python3\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/koohnjsq6839y7byjfhkh/boring1.png?rlkey=q8kzg7wb5p3fqfrcoik49z3w9&st=pba8o95y&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs several tools: git, cmake, ninja-build, clang, and python3. These are commonly used for building and managing software projects.\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone https://boringssl.googlesource.com/boringssl\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/rxcvo8jcuik5d3h1nilkz/boring2.png?rlkey=3day977e2vdo6ljsrvyehrx54&st=z67uqe2y&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the BoringSSL project from Google’s source server. It creates a folder named boringssl with all the files.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd boringssl\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/r01ci1upnklnct42aqvwv/boring3.png?rlkey=4ecly94ics9blimzwekn7w76a&st=kupwyrpt&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves you into the boringssl folder. You can now work with its files.\"}, {\"command\": \"mkdir build && cd build\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/oepzfejl7067el5oq8uil/boring4.png?rlkey=5p8v42z62vionseokgf0r52zl&st=sev3men2&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command creates a folder named build and moves into it. It’s used to keep build files separate from the main source code.\"}, {\"command\": \"cmake -GNinja ..\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/z7h3zmk58evm7navuaxvc/boring5.png?rlkey=oqodm1hi399gdjbl7f00fpwy7&st=yt1osy5j&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command sets up the build system using CMake and tells it to use Ninja to build. It uses the source code from the folder above (..).\"}, {\"command\": \"ninja\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/6njb8g2mk6vndzusjh9bl/boring6.png?rlkey=em1520p2bih7026y3guk0abxe&st=rd22hcti&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command builds the project using the Ninja build system. It compiles the source code into executable files.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"sha256_demo.c\\n====================\\n\\n#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <string.h>\\n#include <openssl/sha.h>\\n\\nvoid print_hex(const unsigned char *data, size_t length) {\\n    for (size_t i = 0; i < length; i++) {\\n        printf(\\\"%02x\\\", data[i]);\\n    }\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n}\\n\\nint main() {\\n    const char *input = \\\"Hello, BoringSSL!\\\";\\n    unsigned char hash[SHA256_DIGEST_LENGTH];\\n    \\n    printf(\\\"Calculating SHA-256 hash for: \\\\\\\"%s\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\", input);\\n    \\n    SHA256((const unsigned char *)input, strlen(input), hash);\\n    \\n    printf(\\\"SHA-256 hash: \\\");\\n    print_hex(hash, SHA256_DIGEST_LENGTH);\\n    \\n    return 0;\\n}\\n\\n\\nCMakeLists.txt\\n==================\\n\\ncmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.0)\\nproject(BoringSSL_Demo)\\n\\n# Find the BoringSSL libraries\\nfind_package(OpenSSL REQUIRED)\\n\\n# Add the demo executable\\nadd_executable(sha256_demo sha256_demo.c)\\n\\n# Link against BoringSSL\'s crypto library\\ntarget_link_libraries(sha256_demo crypto)\", \"explanation\": \"To run the SHA-256 demo in BoringSSL, first create a new folder named `demo` inside the root directory of BoringSSL. In this `demo` folder, create two files: `sha256_demo.c` and `CMakeLists.txt`, then paste the provided code into the appropriate file. After setting up the files, compile the demo by running the following commands inside the `demo` directory: `mkdir build`, then `cd build`, followed by `cmake -GNinja ..` and `ninja`. Make sure all these steps are done within the `demo` folder, or else the build will fail with errors. Once compiled, you can run the demo to see how SHA-256 hashing works using BoringSSL.\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/sma0mcpldo17zcb7dhrn4/boringssl_testing.png?rlkey=dwhz7shzhkpj47x9xrl0ws4zw&st=5dzfcevf&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The image shows a terminal output demonstrating the use of BoringSSL to compute a SHA-256 cryptographic hash.  \\nIt takes the input message *\\\"Hello, BoringSSL!\\\"* and generates its corresponding 64-character hexadecimal digest.  \\nThis test confirms that BoringSSL is correctly implementing the SHA-256 algorithm for secure hashing.  \\nBoringSSL is a lightweight cryptography library, often used in high-performance applications like Google\'s infrastructure.  \\nThis example highlights the library\'s ability to provide robust cryptographic functionality efficiently.\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(3,'botan','Botan','Jack Lloyd','C++','3.7.1','05-02-2025','Open Source License',1,'https://github.com/randombit/botan',1,'\"Kyber, Dilithium, SPHINCS+, McEliece\"','Botan is an open-source cryptography library written in C++ that supports a wide range of modern cryptographic algorithms, including symmetric encryption (like AES), public-key cryptography (like RSA and ECC), hash functions (such as SHA-2 and SHA-3), message authentication codes, key derivation functions, and TLS support. It also includes support for post-quantum algorithms like Kyber and Falcon. Botan is designed to be portable, easy to use, and suitable for desktop, server, and embedded systems. It follows modern standards and is commonly used in security software, research, and education.','The Botan cryptography library does not have a fixed limit on how many random bits it can generate. Users can request any number of random bits using its random number generator (RNG) functions such as rng.randomize().\n\nHowever, there is one important limitation related to fork safety on Unix or Linux systems. Botan uses the process ID (PID) to detect when a program has been copied using the fork() function. The PID is usually a 16-bit number, which means it can hold values from 0 to 65,535. If a program forks many times and the PID number repeats (called PID wrap), Botan may not detect the change and will not reseed the RNG. This can cause the random output to become predictable or reused, which is a security risk. Because of this, Botan recommends manual reseeding after every fork operation to make sure the RNG stays safe.','[{\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/randombit/botan.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/9tq2quwf323963gughy8i/1botan.png?rlkey=whzk23vqvivvzk5em6ysrc73j&st=tzsp4quc&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the botan project from GitHub to your computer. It creates a folder named botan with all the project files.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd botan\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/ektms5pnt0vecbnw34hvg/2botan.png?rlkey=qdg5fdcob8da56rsy7qhmmqvv&st=5o9glxao&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves you into the botan folder. You can now work with the files inside that project.\"}, {\"command\": \"python3 configure.py \\\\\\n  --prefix=/usr/local \\\\\\n  --enable-modules=kyber,xmss \\\\\\n  --disable-modules=everything \\\\\\n  --cc=gcc\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/xf4f4bkpax44aqvgnvm7s/3botan.png?rlkey=nlcuezlmrk27r6ioyxz92yjy1&st=gmtih62h&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command configures the Botan library before building it. It sets the install location, enables only kyber and xmss modules, disables all others, and tells it to use the GCC compiler.\"}, {\"command\": \"make -j4\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/teric4407vpxvbsw1122u/4botan.png?rlkey=4ausuhr2ubgvkfv4922y2043h&st=pet8bc2m&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the project using 4 CPU cores at the same time. It makes the build process faster.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/um7nzivrk1zlfegs3weis/5botan.png?rlkey=kfvd9jxchdf6d1c3hnui54a4r&st=dy048fkr&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the compiled project into your system folders. sudo gives permission to do this as an admin. As a temporary fix because the installation was done in a non-default location.\"}, {\"command\": \"export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/usr/local/lib:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/qq8sq1hg9k3dpx7mfkapw/6botan.png?rlkey=bl2ney58tfs3j6e6wjc62rkx4&st=04nxvu6f&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command tells the system to also look in `/usr/local/lib` for libraries when running programs. It helps fix errors if libraries can\'t be found. As a temporary fix because the installation was done in a non-default location.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <botan/auto_rng.h>\\n#include <botan/rsa.h>\\n#include <botan/pkcs8.h>   // Required for PKCS8::PEM_encode\\n#include <botan/x509_key.h> // Required for X509::PEM_encode\\n#include <iostream>\\n\\nint main() {\\n    try {\\n        Botan::AutoSeeded_RNG rng;\\n\\n        // Generate RSA private key (2048 bits)\\n        Botan::RSA_PrivateKey private_key(rng, 2048);\\n\\n        // Encode and display private key in PEM format\\n        std::string private_key_pem = Botan::PKCS8::PEM_encode(private_key);\\n        std::cout << private_key_pem;\\n\\n        // Encode and display public key in PEM format\\n        std::string public_key_pem = Botan::X509::PEM_encode(private_key);\\n        std::cout << public_key_pem;\\n\\n    } catch (std::exception& e) {\\n        std::cerr << \\\"Error: \\\" << e.what() << \\\"\\\\n\\\";\\n    }\\n\\n    return 0;\\n}\", \"explanation\": \"This is a simple example code that shows how to use Botan to generate a public and private key pair. To compile it, use the command: `g++ -std=c++20 keygen_display.cpp -I/usr/local/include/botan-3 -L/usr/local/lib -lbotan-3 -o keygen_display`. Then, run the program using: `./keygen_display` .It will generate and display the private and public keys.\\n\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/6slki475cltxoqxwtbgqu/testingbotan.png?rlkey=5q22kpxmprexmrralo5x16u38&st=ppml69iw&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This image displays a pair of cryptographic keys, specifically a private key and a public key. The private key is enclosed within the markers `-----BEGIN PRIVATE KEY-----` and `-----END PRIVATE KEY-----`, while the public key is similarly marked with `-----BEGIN PUBLIC KEY-----` and `-----END PUBLIC KEY-----`. These keys are typically used in secure communication protocols to encrypt and decrypt data, ensuring confidentiality and integrity.\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(4,'bouncycastle','Bouncy Castle','Legion of Bouncy Castle Inc.','Java, C#, C++','1.79','31-10-2024','MIT, Bouncy Castle License',1,'https://github.com/bcgit/bc-java',1,'\"Kyber, Dilithium, SPHINCS+\"','Bouncy Castle is a comprehensive and widely adopted cryptographic library for Java and C#, providing a broad range of cryptographic primitives, key management, secure communication protocols, certificate handling, and support for both modern and legacy standards. It is used extensively in enterprise, government, and open-source projects, offering strong support for public-key infrastructure (PKI), X.509 certificates, cryptographic signatures, encryption algorithms, and secure random number generation. The library is maintained by a dedicated team and has a strong reputation for code quality, interoperability, and compliance with various standards, making it a go-to solution for developers in the Java and .NET ecosystems.','Bouncy Castle can have performance bottlenecks compared to native code libraries due to its Java/C# implementation, and may not leverage hardware acceleration available on some platforms. Its extensive API and feature set can present a steep learning curve for new users, and developers may face challenges when integrating it into complex systems that require advanced configuration or interoperability with other cryptographic toolkits. Some advanced features, such as support for FIPS certification or integration with hardware security modules, are only available in commercial editions or require additional setup, which may limit its use in regulated environments. Furthermore, the library’s sheer breadth can result in larger binary sizes and increased dependency management complexity for projects that only require a small subset of its features.','[{\"command\": \"wget https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/org/bouncycastle/bcprov-jdk18on/1.81/bcprov-jdk18on-1.81.jar\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/dhzf9s6pqu6769519mnx2/1.png?rlkey=vwq6cvr1wf0c0h414h7p30ub9&st=81dcpc98&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command uses \\\"wget\\\" to download the Bouncy Castle library file \\\"bcprov-jdk18on-1.81.jar\\\" from the Maven repository. It saves the file into the current directory for use in Java projects.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo apt install openjdk-17-jdk maven\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/08ir8z6p74udwyopv1ev5/2.png?rlkey=zjkbnh3x3mm7b9esnflmgfu6c&st=dfm1n98q&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the Java Development Kit (JDK) version 17 and Apache Maven on a Debian-based Linux system. sudo gives administrator permission, and apt is the package manager used to install the required software.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo apt install gradle\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/mw65rfcpdqgadt5s4p6wq/3.png?rlkey=ldx0cghyx6ixnccfj5zpr4ggz&st=7j08k96y&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs Gradle, a build automation tool, on a Debian-based Linux system. Make sure to use Gradle version 8.7 or the latest version for best compatibility and features.\"}, {\"command\": \"wget https://services.gradle.org/distributions/gradle-8.8-bin.zip\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/lsxn7y4sn4gs55tj4xmbn/4.png?rlkey=lplnj7kylbtohb6nc3o010ch2&st=q996pap3&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the Gradle 8.8 binary zip file from the official Gradle distribution site. It is used to manually install Gradle version 8.8.\"}, {\"command\": \"unzip gradle-8.8-bin.zip -d $HOME/opt\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/ahwc3m72is9efdqdx9tcr/5.png?rlkey=41fyqglg5a7sfwyqu5jq2irhu&st=kbrj7dv1&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command extracts the contents of the gradle-8.8-bin.zip file into the opt directory inside the user\'s home folder. This is part of manually setting up Gradle 8.8.\"}, {\"command\": \"export PATH=$HOME/opt/gradle-8.8/bin:$PATH\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/23y62tu7lh4cpe9f0nd2q/6.png?rlkey=bm6suw5ilp2w4iujxpmovje2b&st=n7yct80b&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command adds the Gradle 8.8 bin directory to the system’s PATH variable, so you can run the gradle command from anywhere in the terminal.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"import org.bouncycastle.jcajce.spec.MLKEMParameterSpec;\\nimport org.bouncycastle.jce.provider.BouncyCastleProvider;\\nimport java.security.*;\\n\\npublic class MLKEMDemo {\\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\\n        Security.addProvider(new BouncyCastleProvider());\\n\\n        // Use ML-KEM (Kyber) with the Bouncy Castle provider\\n        KeyPairGenerator kpg = KeyPairGenerator.getInstance(\\\"ML-KEM\\\", \\\"BC\\\");\\n        kpg.initialize(MLKEMParameterSpec.ml_kem_512, new SecureRandom());\\n        KeyPair kp = kpg.generateKeyPair();\\n\\n        System.out.println(\\\"Public Key: \\\" + kp.getPublic());\\n        System.out.println(\\\"Private Key: \\\" + kp.getPrivate());\\n    }\\n}\", \"explanation\": \"This is the source code that can be used to generate a keypair using the Bouncy Castle library, similar to the one shown in the image. Before running this code, there are a few steps you need to follow. One important step is to make sure the build path of your Java project is properly connected to the Bouncy Castle library. This is necessary so that all the required classes and functions from the library can be used without errors during compilation or execution.\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/96xo2y1xt2uqoflo24j6z/testing_bouncycastle.png?rlkey=uolilla7vpckw17ulgd7yrnvg&st=o4613ojm&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The image above shows the result after generating a keypair using the MLKEM-512 algorithm. It shows the public key and private key that were successfully created.\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(5,'cryptlib','Cryptlib','Peter Gutmann','C','3.4.9','20-02-2026','Proprietary / Open source dual',1,'https://github.com/cryptlib/cryptlib',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','cryptlib is a portable, cross-platform security toolkit that provides a wide spectrum of cryptographic services, including symmetric and asymmetric encryption, digital signatures, key management, and secure network communication protocols. It is designed to be modular and highly configurable, making it suitable for a variety of applications ranging from desktop and server environments to embedded systems. cryptlib aims to simplify the development of secure systems by offering a unified interface and abstracting away much of the complexity involved in managing cryptographic operations, key storage, and protocol negotiation. Its emphasis on portability allows it to run on nearly any platform, including Windows, Unix, Linux, and embedded operating systems.','cryptlib suffers from a relatively small user and developer community, which can result in limited peer review, fewer third-party integrations, and less frequent security updates compared to mainstream libraries like OpenSSL or Bouncy Castle. Documentation may not be as extensive, and finding community support or troubleshooting guidance can be more challenging. Additionally, while cryptlib covers a wide range of cryptographic needs, it may not always provide the latest or most efficient algorithms, and its interfaces may not align with modern best practices or recent compliance requirements, potentially limiting its appeal for new security-critical projects.','[{\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/cryptlib/cryptlib.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/m4kepyhn3597891z0ithv/cryptlib0.png?rlkey=am53syr0nn7vn69xbe84u4dp5&st=6pqko8l1&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the cryptlib project from GitHub. It creates a folder with all the project files.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd cryptlib\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/kzehk979e9d4dsar35f3t/cryptlib1.png?rlkey=ohd9rkdwy40atnvqpq41c90zu&st=p0ev94xk&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves you into the cryptlib folder. You can now access and work with its files.\"}, {\"command\": \"make shared\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/x9otu9wltwbar1zx7wuzq/cryptlib2.png?rlkey=yu3esvlc6kyt62m9l606pundc&st=rnu5w0lh&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command builds the project as a shared library. A shared library can be used by other programs at runtime.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/vcicibxkw6iuvu2imnkvf/cryptlib3.png?rlkey=8ljxtentak7fy0xkona6a5rei&st=92eqddme&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the built shared library into your system folders. sudo gives it the needed admin permission.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <string.h>\\n#include \\\"cryptlib.h\\\"\\n\\nint main(void) {\\n    int status;\\n\\n    // Initialize cryptlib\\n    status = cryptInit();\\n    if (status != CRYPT_OK) {\\n        printf(\\\"cryptInit() failed: %d\\\\n\\\", status);\\n        return 1;\\n    }\\n    printf(\\\"✔ cryptlib initialized successfully.\\\\n\\\");\\n\\n    // Create AES encryption context\\n    CRYPT_CONTEXT aesContext;\\n    status = cryptCreateContext(&aesContext, CRYPT_UNUSED, CRYPT_ALGO_AES);\\n    if (status != CRYPT_OK) {\\n        printf(\\\"cryptCreateContext() failed: %d\\\\n\\\", status);\\n        cryptEnd();\\n        return 1;\\n    }\\n    printf(\\\"✔ AES context created.\\\\n\\\");\\n\\n    // Set AES mode to ECB (must be done BEFORE setting key)\\n    int mode = CRYPT_MODE_ECB;\\n    status = cryptSetAttribute(aesContext, CRYPT_CTXINFO_MODE, mode);\\n    if (status != CRYPT_OK) {\\n        printf(\\\"cryptSetAttribute(MODE) failed: %d\\\\n\\\", status);\\n        cryptDestroyContext(aesContext);\\n        cryptEnd();\\n        return 1;\\n    }\\n\\n    // Set a 128-bit key (16 bytes)\\n    const unsigned char key[16] = \\\"mysecretkey12345\\\";\\n    status = cryptSetAttributeString(aesContext, CRYPT_CTXINFO_KEY, key, 16);\\n    if (status != CRYPT_OK) {\\n        printf(\\\"cryptSetAttributeString(KEY) failed: %d\\\\n\\\", status);\\n        cryptDestroyContext(aesContext);\\n        cryptEnd();\\n        return 1;\\n    }\\n\\n    // Message to encrypt (16 bytes, block-aligned)\\n    unsigned char plaintext[32] = \\\"HelloCryptlib!!!\\\";  // 16 bytes\\n    unsigned char ciphertext[32];\\n    unsigned char decrypted[32];\\n    int length = 16;\\n\\n    // Encrypt\\n    memcpy(ciphertext, plaintext, length);\\n    status = cryptEncrypt(aesContext, ciphertext, length);\\n    if (status != CRYPT_OK) {\\n        printf(\\\"cryptEncrypt() failed: %d\\\\n\\\", status);\\n        cryptDestroyContext(aesContext);\\n        cryptEnd();\\n        return 1;\\n    }\\n\\n    printf(\\\"✔ Data encrypted.\\\\n? Encrypted: \\\");\\n    for (int i = 0; i < length; i++) {\\n        printf(\\\"%02X \\\", ciphertext[i]);\\n    }\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n\\n    // Decrypt\\n    memcpy(decrypted, ciphertext, length);\\n    status = cryptDecrypt(aesContext, decrypted, length);\\n    if (status != CRYPT_OK) {\\n        printf(\\\"cryptDecrypt() failed: %d\\\\n\\\", status);\\n        cryptDestroyContext(aesContext);\\n        cryptEnd();\\n        return 1;\\n    }\\n\\n    decrypted[length] = \'\\\\0\';  // Null-terminate after decryption\\n\\n    printf(\\\"✔ Data decrypted.\\\\n? Decrypted: %s\\\\n\\\", decrypted);\\n\\n    // Clean up\\n    cryptDestroyContext(aesContext);\\n    cryptEnd();\\n    printf(\\\"✔ cryptlib shut down.\\\\n\\\");\\n\\n    return 0;\\n}\", \"explanation\": \"To run the program, first compile it with gcc test_cryptlib.c -I. -L. -lcl -o test_cryptlib, then set the library path using export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=., and finally run it with ./test_cryptlib. \"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/b3i1hsgdg0rt5puv8mrel/testing_cryptlib.png?rlkey=4u56mos4mii1soouju753wgsy&st=fajwqlhn&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This C program demonstrates a simple AES-128 encryption and decryption using the cryptlib library in ECB mode: it initializes the library, creates an AES context with a fixed 128-bit key (\\\"mysecretkey12345\\\"), encrypts the 16-byte message \\\"HelloCryptlib!!!\\\" and prints the ciphertext in hexadecimal, then decrypts it back to the original message and prints it. While this shows the basic steps to use cryptlib, ECB mode is not secure because it does not use randomness and produces the same encrypted result for identical text; for better security, modes like GCM or CBC with a proper initialization vector should be used.\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(6,'cryptopp','Crypto++\n','Wei Dai (Community)','C++','9.0','10-01-2025','Boost License 1.0',1,'https://github.com/weidai11/cryptopp',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','Crypto++ is a mature, open-source C++ library offering a vast array of cryptographic algorithms, including block ciphers, stream ciphers, hash functions, public-key cryptography, and authenticated encryption schemes. It is widely used in academic research, security product development, and open-source projects for its flexibility, completeness, and active maintenance. Crypto++ includes numerous reference implementations of both established and emerging algorithms, providing a valuable resource for both learning and secure application development. The library is well-documented, with many code samples, and is highly configurable for advanced users who need fine-grained cryptographic control.','Crypto++ can be quite complex for beginners due to its extensive API, template-heavy code, and reliance on advanced C++ features, which can lead to a steep learning curve and potential portability issues across different compilers and platforms. The library does not hold official FIPS validation, which may be a requirement for some regulated industries or government use. While it offers many algorithms, the sheer number can result in larger binaries and more complex dependency management. Its performance, while generally good, may not match highly optimized or hardware-accelerated alternatives for certain algorithms or use cases.','[{\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/weidai11/cryptopp.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/00tdwn7apydreiq6puew0/cryptopp0.png?rlkey=o00v2dwzp9w2ifk2cl11yuf93&st=ds7v3a0f&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the Crypto++ project from GitHub. It creates a folder named cryptopp with all the project files.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd cryptopp\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/8mph97yyg39hmp5u2l12k/cryptopp1.png?rlkey=60ceovxafeb1e1pmmfv7n6wfg&st=170veemd&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves you into the cryptopp folder. You can now work with the project files inside.\"}, {\"command\": \"make -j$(nproc)\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/zxhdrvd4twqrzj76poa7i/cryptopp2.png?rlkey=az0v3eb5o5pxddgaj09u7kif3&st=6du20k6r&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the project using all available CPU cores. It speeds up the build process.\"}, {\"command\": \"make test\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/f71fm0q0qr8qlwzhx17ab/cryptopp3.png?rlkey=dyzyr1gldyauhghd99rfmhoi5&st=tyvk6yya&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command runs the built-in tests for the project. It checks if everything is working correctly after the build.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/bq4ukqzrcqa5mqwnm9g2f/cryptopp4.png?rlkey=f1r9bhkepdibylv1xqaszanee&st=pwyzy0ew&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the compiled Crypto++ library to your system. It needs sudo to place files in system directories.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <iostream>\\n#include <string>\\n#include <cryptopp/aes.h>\\n#include <cryptopp/modes.h>\\n#include <cryptopp/filters.h>\\n#include <cryptopp/hex.h>\\n#include <cryptopp/osrng.h>\\n\\n// Add this to use CryptoPP names without prefix\\nusing namespace CryptoPP;\\n\\nint main() {\\n    try {\\n        // Generate a random key and IV (Initialization Vector)\\n        AutoSeededRandomPool prng;\\n        \\n        // AES uses 16, 24, or 32 byte keys\\n        byte key[AES::DEFAULT_KEYLENGTH];\\n        prng.GenerateBlock(key, sizeof(key));\\n        \\n        byte iv[AES::BLOCKSIZE];\\n        prng.GenerateBlock(iv, sizeof(iv));\\n        \\n        std::string plaintext = \\\"Hello, Crypto++! This is a simple AES-CBC example.\\\";\\n        std::string ciphertext, decryptedtext;\\n        \\n        // Print original message\\n        std::cout << \\\"Original message: \\\" << plaintext << std::endl;\\n        \\n        // Encrypt\\n        {\\n            CBC_Mode<AES>::Encryption encryptor;\\n            encryptor.SetKeyWithIV(key, sizeof(key), iv);\\n            \\n            StringSource ss1(plaintext, true,\\n                new StreamTransformationFilter(encryptor,\\n                    new StringSink(ciphertext)\\n                )\\n            );\\n        }\\n        \\n        // Print encrypted message in hex\\n        std::string encoded;\\n        StringSource ss2(ciphertext, true,\\n            new HexEncoder(\\n                new StringSink(encoded)\\n            )\\n        );\\n        std::cout << \\\"Encrypted (hex): \\\" << encoded << std::endl;\\n        \\n        // Decrypt\\n        {\\n            CBC_Mode<AES>::Decryption decryptor;\\n            decryptor.SetKeyWithIV(key, sizeof(key), iv);\\n            \\n            StringSource ss3(ciphertext, true,\\n                new StreamTransformationFilter(decryptor,\\n                    new StringSink(decryptedtext)\\n                )\\n            );\\n        }\\n        \\n        // Print decrypted message\\n        std::cout << \\\"Decrypted: \\\" << decryptedtext << std::endl;\\n        \\n    } catch(const Exception& e) {\\n        std::cerr << \\\"Crypto++ error: \\\" << e.what() << std::endl;\\n        return 1;\\n    }\\n    \\n    return 0;\\n}\", \"explanation\": \"You can use the following command to compile the program:\\n`g++ -o aes_example aes_example.cpp -lcryptopp`.\\n\\nThis command will create an executable file named `aes_example` from the `aes_example.cpp` source code. It also links the Crypto++ library, which is needed for the AES functions in the program. After compiling, you can run the program to see how AES encryption and decryption work in the demo. This will help you understand how data can be secured using AES in a real application.\\n\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/wonaxtffdnhmx27mjchsx/cryptopp_testing.png?rlkey=qy00oyp9vk271snice16lk49a&st=hfhw8kep&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The image shows a successful test of AES encryption in CBC mode using the Crypto++ library.  \\nIt demonstrates how plaintext is encrypted and then correctly decrypted back to its original form.  \\nThe output confirms that the encryption process is working properly and data integrity is preserved.  \\nCrypto++ is a widely used C++ library for cryptographic operations, especially in performance-sensitive applications.  \\nThis test highlights the reliability of symmetric encryption for securing sensitive data.\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(7,'fastcrypto','fastcrypto','Mysten Labs','Rust','0.1.2','06-05-2025','Apache 2.0',1,'https://github.com/MystenLabs/fastcrypto',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','fastcrypto is a cryptographic library designed for scenarios where performance is critical, such as high-frequency trading, blockchain, or high-throughput networking applications. It employs a combination of hardware acceleration, low-level optimization, and minimal abstraction layers to achieve rapid cryptographic operations, particularly for commonly used algorithms. The library aims to deliver speed and efficiency, reducing latency and computational overhead, and is typically integrated into systems where every microsecond counts and cryptographic strength cannot be compromised for performance.','While fastcrypto excels in performance, its algorithm selection is more limited compared to general-purpose libraries, focusing only on the most commonly used and hardware-accelerated primitives. This trade-off means fastcrypto might not support all cryptographic standards or legacy systems, reducing its flexibility for diverse applications. Its low-level optimizations can introduce portability challenges, as routines may rely on specific CPU instruction sets or hardware features, and documentation may lag behind rapid development, making it difficult for new users to integrate or troubleshoot. Security reviews may also be less extensive than for larger, more widely adopted libraries, raising potential concerns over code robustness in edge cases.','[{\"command\": \"sudo apt install -y \\\\\\n    git \\\\\\n    curl \\\\\\n    build-essential \\\\\\n    pkg-config \\\\\\n    libssl-dev \\\\\\n    cmake\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/vszwun0yhf9pfbqnsfyiq/fastcrypto0.png?rlkey=4vxmfsox3wufi962c09w199p2&st=szhau5a4&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs common development tools and libraries like git, curl, cmake, and libssl-dev. These are needed to build and manage many software projects.\"}, {\"command\": \"curl --proto \'=https\' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/l1ulh5qv6somv0q7kzor1/fastcrypto2.png?rlkey=en2ky33b2oduv2ir5buo9y9n6&st=mzrhr78e&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads and runs the Rust installer script. It sets up the Rust programming language on your system. If the command as for an option, press enter to continue default configuration.\"}, {\"command\": \"source $HOME/.cargo/env\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/x860b01asq2j1db1pfns1/fastcrypto3.png?rlkey=p4rsqeoj5iokztqk0ofrtzldh&st=hjrn5e8f&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command updates your terminal session to recognize Rust commands. It allows you to use cargo and rustc right away.\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/MystenLabs/fastcrypto.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/gfmizmtawllsi6rsy364f/fastcrypto4.png?rlkey=vkc7dezwarsrq9gg8mngfqhhw&st=qk7xe459&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the fastcrypto project from GitHub. It creates a folder with all the project files.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd fastcrypto\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/0mkzv202rrpd9lrv09z8k/fastcrypto5.png?rlkey=o6dzk6896in9o31e3s5vn438w&st=pdv3529n&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves you into the fastcrypto folder. You can now work with its files.\"}, {\"command\": \"cargo build --release\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/s8kka21boghhx59b9eadu/fastcrypto6.png?rlkey=iwa9gcugbekiccbwiyaltbs3v&st=zxymsprx&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the fastcrypto project in release mode. It creates an optimized version of the program.\"}, {\"command\": \"cargo test --release\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/2378e33zqpcut7qnf8vhq/fastcrypto7.png?rlkey=ln3ycpn50iwcpvu4uq77j49z6&st=bgmcxqja&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command runs all the tests for fastcrypto in release mode. It checks if everything works correctly.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"src/main.rs\\n=========================\\n\\nuse fastcrypto::hash::{Sha256, HashFunction};\\n\\nfn main() {\\n    let message = b\\\"Hello from Sui\'s fastcrypto!\\\";\\n    let digest = Sha256::digest(message);\\n    println!(\\\"Message: {}\\\", String::from_utf8_lossy(message));\\n    println!(\\\"Digest: {}\\\", digest);\\n}\\n\\n\\nCargo.toml\\n=========================\\n\\n[package]\\nname = \\\"fastcrypto-test\\\"\\nversion = \\\"0.1.0\\\"\\nedition = \\\"2021\\\"\\n\\n[dependencies]\\nfastcrypto = { path = \\\"/home/fikri/Desktop/fastcrypto/fastcrypto\\\" }\", \"explanation\": \"This Rust program demonstrates how to use the `fastcrypto` library to compute a SHA-256 hash.  \\nIt hashes the message *\\\"Hello from Sui\'s fastcrypto!\\\"* and prints both the original message and its digest.  \\nThe `fastcrypto` crate is imported as a local dependency from a custom path in `Cargo.toml`.  \\nThe code uses the `Sha256::digest()` method to generate a secure hash efficiently.  \\n\\nThe `src/main.rs` file contains the main application code, where the hashing logic is implemented.  \\nThe `Cargo.toml` file is the project\'s manifest, defining metadata like name, version, and dependencies—here, it includes `fastcrypto` as a local crate.  \\nTogether, these two files form a complete Rust project that can be built and run using Cargo, Rust’s package manager.  \\nThis example shows a simple and safe way to handle cryptographic hashing in Rust.\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/ukgphbuzrx73c33hjohgt/fastcrypt_testing.png?rlkey=d8mcl56co5yxmjo1zvx5vqv9n&st=tl34qnp1&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The image shows a terminal output from a Rust program testing the FastCrypto library.  \\nIt displays the result of computing a SHA-256 hash on the message \\\"Hello from Sui\'s fastcrypto!\\\".  \\nThe program successfully generates a unique cryptographic digest, confirming the hashing process works correctly.  \\nThe test was run in release mode, which ensures optimized and efficient performance.  \\nThis demonstrates a reliable and secure way to use cryptographic functions in Rust applications.\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(8,'jsrsasign','jsrsasign','Kenji Urushima','JavaScript','11.1.3','18-04-2026','MIT',1,'https://github.com/kjur/jsrsasign',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','jsrsasign is a popular JavaScript library designed for cryptographic signing, verification, and key management directly in web browsers and Node.js environments. It enables developers to implement PKI features such as digital signatures, certificate validation, and JWT processing for secure web applications without relying on back-end servers. With its focus on browser compatibility, jsrsasign is widely used in client-side security scenarios, such as single sign-on and secure form submissions.','jsrsasign is inherently limited by the security and performance restrictions of JavaScript and browser environments. Client-side cryptography can expose sensitive operations to potential attacks, including code tampering and memory inspection. The library is not suitable for high-security or server-side cryptographic tasks, and its algorithm selection, while broad, may not keep pace with all the latest security standards or recommended practices.','[{\"command\": \"sudo apt install -y nodejs npm\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/mdaz5l9fy6x89mtlxh5wc/jsrasign0.png?rlkey=yzbtqwmo9u0gp9dxxel7qvdd6&st=ku88dekk&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs Node.js and npm on the system. Node.js allows you to run JavaScript outside of a web browser, and npm is the package manager used to install JavaScript libraries. The -y option automatically agrees to the installation without asking for confirmation.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo npm install -g jsrsasign\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/0c4q5mrr3hmrgtxjqwivx/jsrasign1.2.png?rlkey=121wxrqhlriww3f1d69l8leng&st=uqvnchv1&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the jsrsasign library globally on your system using npm. Installing it globally means you can use the library in any project without installing it again. The -g option tells npm to make the package available system-wide.\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/kjur/jsrsasign.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/ejrwgtre7fajqjvru6okb/jsrasign2.png?rlkey=fkaghy1nhi7gw9kala4h25hqk&st=aogbavj0&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"ChatGPT said:\\n\\nThis command downloads the jsrsasign project from GitHub to your computer. The git clone part tells Git to copy the entire repository, and the URL points to the project’s location on GitHub. After running it, a new folder named jsrsasign will appear in your current directory containing all the source files.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd jsrsasign\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/ogf82qcbwentc3ewr0zzx/jsrasign3.png?rlkey=948b7mtqod6oa00bpu4xayabk&st=pitq4jz0&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command changes the current working directory to the jsrsasign folder. It allows you to work inside that folder so you can run commands or edit files related to the jsrsasign project.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"// Load the jsrsasign library\\nconst rs = require(\'jsrsasign\');\\n\\n// Create key pair\\nconst kp = rs.KEYUTIL.generateKeypair(\\\"RSA\\\", 1024);\\nconst prvKey = kp.prvKeyObj;\\nconst pubKey = kp.pubKeyObj;\\n\\n// Message to sign\\nconst message = \\\"Hello from jsrsasign!\\\";\\n\\n// Sign the message\\nconst sig = new rs.KJUR.crypto.Signature({ alg: \\\"SHA256withRSA\\\" });\\nsig.init(prvKey);\\nsig.updateString(message);\\nconst signatureHex = sig.sign();\\n\\n// Verify the signature\\nconst verify = new rs.KJUR.crypto.Signature({ alg: \\\"SHA256withRSA\\\" });\\nverify.init(pubKey);\\nverify.updateString(message);\\nconst isValid = verify.verify(signatureHex);\\n\\n// Output results\\nconsole.log(\\\"Message:\\\", message);\\nconsole.log(\\\"Signature (hex):\\\", signatureHex);\\nconsole.log(\\\"Signature valid?\\\", isValid);\\n\", \"explanation\": \"To run the code, simply use node test.js command after create the file.This code uses the jsrsasign library to create and verify a digital signature. It first generates an RSA key pair, then signs a message using the private key. Finally, it checks the signature with the public key and shows whether it is valid.\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/yzc1qpeczywgrhgwo4dvr/jsrasigntesting.png?rlkey=e22tga0fwczbh1q1xqqn84ris&st=k68mv5nx&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The image shows a successful test of the jsrsasign cryptographic library in Node.js, where executing test.js generates a message (\\\"Hello from jsrsasign!\\\") and its corresponding digital signature in hexadecimal format. The lengthy hex string (e.g., b6a14737...) represents a secure cryptographic signature (likely RSA or ECDSA), and the output Signature valid? true confirms the library correctly generated and verified the signature, proving both the signing and verification functions work as intended. This test validates that the library can create tamper-proof signatures and authenticate them—a core requirement for secure data transmission or document signing.\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(9,'libgcrypt','Libgcrypt','GNU Project','C','1.11','13-05-2025','LGPL',1,'https://github.com/gpg/libgcrypt',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','Libgcrypt is a foundational cryptographic library used by many open-source tools and systems, providing implementations of cryptographic primitives such as block ciphers, hashes, MACs, and random number generators. Based on the core of GnuPG, it is designed for use as a backend for higher-level cryptographic protocols and security products, rather than direct end-user interaction. Libgcrypt is highly portable and benefits from active maintenance and security auditing.','Libgcrypt does not implement full cryptographic protocols or application-level features such as SSL/TLS; it requires developers to assemble low-level primitives into secure constructions, which can be error-prone and insecure if not done rigorously. Its API can be challenging for newcomers, and there is a risk that incorrect use could lead to vulnerabilities. It also may lack some optimizations or features found in specialized protocol libraries.','[{\"command\": \"sudo apt install -y build-essential automake libtool pkg-config texinfo fig2dev\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/e0jr7pvgjbt2ua9h8ku3f/libgcrypt0.png?rlkey=8buwrsvxt0luoj7jeutj2qozp&st=mzermlu5&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs several important development tools on Ubuntu.\\nIt includes compilers, build systems, and document tools needed for compiling programs and creating software packages.\\nIt makes sure your system has all the basic tools required for software development.\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/gpg/libgpg-error.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/eg9puuuz11u0j3uniuixd/libgcrypt1.png?rlkey=anezntjev79cfgi0h8vemehs2&st=3frd80uc&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads a copy of the libgpg-error project from GitHub to your computer.\\nIt creates a new folder named libgpg-error containing all the source code and files from the repository.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd libgpg-error\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/tbtwj8128vfou59bi1xfi/libgcrypt2.png?rlkey=w42mt64cqykit0f3tvx2dugdn&st=ucx7olbk&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves you into the libgpg-error folder so you can work with its files and run commands inside it.\"}, {\"command\": \"./autogen.sh\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/t843lw68tjmv046jnrsnb/libgcrypt3.png?rlkey=0dgshufk4mydfgyuzfhw5glek&st=sb2bzt20&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command runs the autogen.sh script in the current folder.\\nIt prepares the project for building by creating the necessary configuration files.\"}, {\"command\": \"./configure\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/z6eupq8u8woqgtcm4kavx/libgcrypt4.png?rlkey=zpc8ej5ho5k8kwobcingg0g7i&st=3t0rv4cc&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"./configure will check your system for the required tools, libraries, and paths, then generate a Makefile so you can compile libgpg-error.\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/403k3blqknlpc1wrlh6li/libgcrypt5.png?rlkey=rwlk56kiy2rzp90ubrmzkr7ln&st=hurmpli6&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the source code into executable files. It reads the build instructions created by the configure command and uses them to create the program binaries.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/p2ltgtkbgkm2rlucin0l9/libgcrypt6.png?rlkey=fatvr8wi5xhyqt1v2t9am0c5l&st=bsqak135&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the compiled program into your system directories (usually /usr/local/bin, /usr/local/lib, etc.) so it can be used anywhere in the terminal. It requires sudo because it writes to system-level folders.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd ..\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/yqf38p3003htvjbt45k9o/libgcrypt7.png?rlkey=4gxwc1g74nn2zqll18lboe9l7&st=z8nmneov&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves you up one directory from your current location in the terminal.\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/gpg/libgcrypt.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/xwuswople9yhp96ogl6he/libgcrypt8.png?rlkey=4gqadddi2ozgfjuet70ece6m1&st=pw67blgz&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the libgcrypt source code from its official GitHub repository to your current directory.After running it, you will get a new folder called libgcrypt containing all the files from the repository.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd libgcrypt\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/tm37uev9rctkyssdoulft/libgcrypt9.png?rlkey=la6buzkvr42iavixy189vcybu&st=ju7ox9um&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"That command moves you into the libgcrypt directory you just cloned \"}, {\"command\": \"./autogen.sh\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/h2qcdizcgq2fvjjmgztgo/libgcrypt10.png?rlkey=8jqtxqy7zmeo687rpbomoil3e&st=efq4xz3f&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The ./autogen.sh command prepares the build system for the project. It creates or updates the necessary configuration files so the program can be compiled later.\"}, {\"command\": \"./configure --disable-doc\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/bvvc2wy4vjyysq7pmhyi0/libgcrypt11.png?rlkey=82998dz88cytih3ral1zhyi6c&st=n6k5lg87&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The ./configure --disable-doc command sets up the build settings for the program.\\nIt also disables building the documentation files to save time and resources.\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/uroq6tema8krcn20y3jzc/libgcrypt12.png?rlkey=76xslp8geewagnl9plpqsygwt&st=z9f1ao5r&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The make command compiles the source code into executable files.\\nIt follows the instructions from the Makefile created during the configure step.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/sb2obfnxkg37wr9epz8yd/libgcrypt13.png?rlkey=bh0woacv5309b1cb2ltszf33z&st=kxx3bvl8&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The sudo make install command copies the compiled files to the system folders.\\nIt needs sudo to get permission for installing in protected directories.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <gcrypt.h>\\n\\nint main(void) {\\n    // Check libgcrypt version\\n    if (!gcry_check_version(GCRYPT_VERSION)) {\\n        fprintf(stderr, \\\"libgcrypt version mismatch\\\\n\\\");\\n        return 1;\\n    }\\n\\n    // Secure memory setup (needed for some operations)\\n    gcry_control(GCRYCTL_DISABLE_SECMEM, 0);\\n    gcry_control(GCRYCTL_INITIALIZATION_FINISHED, 0);\\n\\n    // Generate random data\\n    unsigned char buffer[16];\\n    gcry_randomize(buffer, sizeof(buffer), GCRY_STRONG_RANDOM);\\n\\n    // Print the random bytes in hex\\n    printf(\\\"Random bytes: \\\");\\n    for (int i = 0; i < sizeof(buffer); i++) {\\n        printf(\\\"%02X\\\", buffer[i]);\\n    }\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n\\n    return 0;\\n}\\n\", \"explanation\": \"You should create the test file inside the ~/Desktop/libgcrypt/testfile directory and ensure that it links to the libgcrypt.so library located in ~/Desktop/libgcrypt/src/.libs/. Since the library is not yet installed system-wide, you need to set the LD_LIBRARY_PATH environment variable to point to ~/Desktop/libgcrypt/src/.libs when running the test program so it can find and load libgcrypt.so correctly.\\n\\ncommand: export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=~/Desktop/libgcrypt/src/.libs:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/ukzz8htiv7bpt7hlx2epw/libgcrypttesting.png?rlkey=aignxxisua8ueaaepvp2kq69w&st=ecdiwoos&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The image shows a successful test of libgcrypt after configuring the LD_LIBRARY_PATH to include the library directory (/Desktop/libgcrypt/src/.libs), where executing the test program (./test) outputs a hexadecimal string (AF187CB7EA99B08DD44219862C6B5C58), confirming proper library linkage and functionality. This random byte sequence (often used for cryptographic keys, encryption nonces, or testing RNG quality) demonstrates that libgcrypt’s core operations—like secure randomness generation—are working as expected. Randomness is vital in cryptography to ensure keys and encrypted data stay unpredictable and secure. (Note the typo in LD_LIBRARY_PATI in the command.)\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(10,'liboqs','liboqs','Open Quantum Safe (OQS)','C/C++','0.15.0','15-11-2025','BSD-Style',1,'https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/liboqs',1,'\"BIKE, Classic McEliece, FrodoKEM, HQC, Kyber, Kyber, NTRU-Prime, CROSS, CRYSTALS-Dilithium, Falcon, MAYO, Dilithium, SNOVA, SPHINCS+, UOV,  XMSS, XMSSMT, LMS\"','liboqs is an open-source library that provides quantum-resistant cryptographic algorithms for key exchange (KEM) and digital signatures, ensuring protection against future quantum computer attacks. It offers a unified API, testing tools, and performance benchmarks, making it easier for developers to integrate post-quantum security into applications. As part of the Open Quantum Safe (OQS) project, supported by the Linux Foundation\'s Post-Quantum Cryptography Alliance, liboqs enables real-world testing in protocols like TLS, X.509, and S/MIME. ','liboqs is designed primarily for research and prototyping of post-quantum cryptography (PQC) algorithms, not for production use, as it may have unresolved security or performance limitations. The library specializes in quantum-resistant cryptographic schemes rather than serving as a general-purpose cryptographic solution. Developers should use it for experimentation and evaluation, not in real-world deployments where mature, standardized cryptography is required.','[{\"command\": \"sudo apt update\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/bhxqx4qzkzvaqns9d9c41/1.png?rlkey=bbb31bc83coij2u2taq56vd0i&st=rgmsj7dr&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command updates the list of available packages and their versions. It ensures your system has the latest package information before installing anything new.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo apt install cmake ninja-build gcc g++ libssl-dev\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/f0jym0i7lff33rn9bkbxu/2.png?rlkey=xcdot17rw3p8znu18k2p0yx2f&st=yu0l60ff&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs essential tools and libraries such as CMake, Ninja (a fast build system), GCC/G++ compilers, and OpenSSL development files for cryptographic support.\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone --recursive https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/liboqs.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/lmvv1vtraip0qr65mo322/3.png?rlkey=viivheczqv1oo1mckboc8ei7e&st=lqe55ogh&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This downloads the liboqs source code from GitHub. The --recursive option ensures all submodules (dependencies) are also downloaded.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd liboqs\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/dc1m6cgq4pczz3yl2b8wg/4.png?rlkey=ka9z0l2qbrbci08yuuczho1km&st=2f0kcmzv&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"Changes the current directory to the downloaded liboqs folder.\"}, {\"command\": \"mkdir build && cd build\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/wt7szqfz9881q1iyyenfx/5.png?rlkey=u423tfwqofx5am7zocjq9jlxz&st=925sm8by&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"Creates a new folder called build inside the project, then moves into it. This folder is used to keep the compiled files separate from the source code.\"}, {\"command\": \"cmake -DOQS_USE_AVX2=OFF ..\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/q1p2bu6b38h8k4va67qeg/6.png?rlkey=plnj7ug4ccjnnmty3mfank7bu&st=h78s28xv&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command runs CMake to configure the build process for liboqs. Option \\\"-DOQS_USE_AVX2=OFF\\\" disables the use of AVX2 instructions, making the build suitable for systems without AVX2 support. The \\\"..\\\" tells CMake to look for the source files in the parent directory.\"}, {\"command\": \"make -j\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/u3csrkddd602saj2cmh19/7.png?rlkey=cqcu4sycco840emp56c7oyinw&st=ebiycok8&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the liboqs library using multiple CPU cores at the same time (parallel build). The -j option speeds up the build process by running several jobs in parallel.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/m79nhs5cf52ibzpumw64b/8.png?rlkey=nl8lur682qt4du0c0x1ntx60r&st=4rcd4azb&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"After running the make command to build the program, sudo make install installs the compiled files into system directories (like /usr/local/bin). It usually requires sudo to get permission to write to these locations.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <stdlib.h>\\n#include <string.h>\\n#include <oqs/oqs.h>\\n\\nint main() {\\n   // Initialize liboqs\\n   OQS_init();\\n\\n   const char *kem_alg = \\\"Kyber512\\\";\\n\\n   // Check if Kyber512 is enabled\\n   if (!OQS_KEM_alg_is_enabled(kem_alg)) {\\n       printf(\\\"Algorithm %s is not enabled!\\\\n\\\", kem_alg);\\n       OQS_destroy();\\n       return EXIT_FAILURE;\\n   }\\n\\n   // Create KEM object\\n   OQS_KEM *kem = OQS_KEM_new(kem_alg);\\n   if (kem == NULL) {\\n       printf(\\\"Failed to create KEM object!\\\\n\\\");\\n       OQS_destroy();\\n       return EXIT_FAILURE;\\n   }\\n\\n   // Allocate memory for public and secret keys\\n   uint8_t *public_key = malloc(kem->length_public_key);\\n   uint8_t *secret_key = malloc(kem->length_secret_key);\\n\\n   if (!public_key || !secret_key) {\\n       printf(\\\"Memory allocation failed!\\\\n\\\");\\n       OQS_KEM_free(kem);\\n       OQS_destroy();\\n       return EXIT_FAILURE;\\n   }\\n\\n   // Generate key pair\\n   if (OQS_KEM_keypair(kem, public_key, secret_key) != OQS_SUCCESS) {\\n       printf(\\\"Key pair generation failed!\\\\n\\\");\\n       free(public_key);\\n       free(secret_key);\\n       OQS_KEM_free(kem);\\n       OQS_destroy();\\n       return EXIT_FAILURE;\\n   }\\n\\n   // Print public key\\n   printf(\\\"Kyber512 Public Key (%zu bytes):\\\\n\\\", kem->length_public_key);\\n   for (size_t i = 0; i < kem->length_public_key; i++) {\\n       printf(\\\"%02x\\\", public_key[i]);\\n   }\\n   printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n\\n   // Print secret key\\n   printf(\\\"Kyber512 Secret Key (%zu bytes):\\\\n\\\", kem->length_secret_key);\\n   for (size_t i = 0; i < kem->length_secret_key; i++) {\\n       printf(\\\"%02x\\\", secret_key[i]);\\n   }\\n   printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n\\n   // Cleanup\\n   free(public_key);\\n   free(secret_key);\\n   OQS_KEM_free(kem);\\n   OQS_destroy();\\n\\n   return EXIT_SUCCESS;\\n}\", \"explanation\": \"Write your code in an IDE/text editor, save it in liboqs/build/tests directory and name it as pqc_test.c, compile with gcc -o pqc_test pqc_test.c -loqs -lssl -lcrypto, and finally run the executable ./pqc_test to test the PQC functionality.\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/xr6aysswjffoqo5yo6svo/liboqs_testing.png?rlkey=9xy1ydpcspu6ilwgx86q3o99s&st=3l74lrci&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This image shows the successful output of the source code above when it compiles and runs correctly without any errors.\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(11,'libsodium','Libsodium','Frank Denis','C','1.0.20','25-05-2023','ISC',1,'https://github.com/jedisct1/libsodium',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','libsodium is a modern, cross-platform cryptographic library designed for ease of use, security, and performance. It offers high-level APIs for authenticated encryption, public key cryptography, hashing, and secure key derivation, abstracting away most of the complexity of cryptography for developers. libsodium is widely adopted and praised for its clear documentation, active community, and strong security posture.','libsodium intentionally omits support for legacy and less secure algorithms, which may be necessary for interoperability with older systems. It focuses on safe-by-default APIs, which can limit flexibility for advanced or custom cryptographic needs, and may not support highly specialized or experimental protocols.','[{\"command\": \"sudo apt install build-essential git autoconf libtool\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/7jyn5bylllaxuol9pk8d9/libsodium0.png?rlkey=v3g18jekx5oekas5b6fd3xzis&st=ojoda2v6&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs several important development tools on a Linux system. The sudo part gives administrator rights to run the installation. The apt install tells the system to download and set up the listed packages. These packages include compilers, Git for version control, and tools like autoconf and libtool for building software from source.\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/jedisct1/libsodium.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/5nbc6ica6g4onbt2tq3l4/libsodium1.png?rlkey=udubvx7fg63w5kxx1rpccfcn5&st=xgh67kqs&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command makes a copy of the **libsodium** project from GitHub onto your computer. The `git clone` part tells Git to download the whole repository, including its history and files. The link after it is the address of the project. After running this, you will have a local folder with all the project files.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd libsodium\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/1tb0afdrtdao23pqp6k9r/libsodium2.png?rlkey=4mvb7go3j563kkocprsu4x5t6&st=nx2a0zmn&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command changes the current working directory to the libsodium folder. The `cd` means \\\"change directory.\\\" It lets you move inside the folder that was created by the previous `git clone` command. After this, all other commands you run will work inside the libsodium folder.\"}, {\"command\": \"git tag -l | grep RELEASE\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/bmwinmvzi5hqdigs0p8hh/libsodium3.png?rlkey=qhg1fugbubuwhtxr6ln04pynb&st=4cdeydy7&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command shows all version tags in the repository that include the word RELEASE. The part git tag -l lists every tag available in the project. The symbol | passes this list to the next command. Then grep RELEASE searches the list and only displays tags that contain RELEASE.\"}, {\"command\": \"git checkout 1.0.20-RELEASE\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/5lfon4vcc5jgcovmjey7m/libsodium4.png?rlkey=he886i3kz928xwbfj6fdi0qpq&st=jcahh6p8&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command switches the project to the version marked as 1.0.20-RELEASE. The git checkout part tells Git to move to a specific branch, commit, or tag. Here it uses the tag 1.0.20-RELEASE. After running this, the project files will match that exact version.\"}, {\"command\": \"./autogen.sh\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/sf10pig47hejx32gftjkn/libsodium5.png?rlkey=r8wkhgbkg73zm09cdf4ethuva&st=3ter71rp&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command runs the autogen.sh script in the current folder. The ./ tells the system to execute a file located in the present directory. The script usually prepares the build system by creating configuration files. It is often the first step before compiling software from source.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"./configure\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/dcbyjyvqxueo6paqkuxg1/libsodium6.png?rlkey=gllgntudxdt6bk7ztlkkj06ya&st=osxa04si&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command runs the configure script in the current folder. It checks your system to see if all needed tools and libraries are available. It also sets up makefiles that tell the system how to build the program. This step prepares the software for the compilation process.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/hx404ux26qj3989qyj9gg/libsodium7.png?rlkey=qhz6qiqa8am7kohdvmuvm0rmb&st=q6qg6f0c&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command starts the process of compiling the source code into executable programs. The make tool reads the instructions from the makefile created by the configure step. It then builds the software step by step using the compiler and other tools. After this, the program files are ready but not yet installed system-wide.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/uepyerw6xnrzc5nj2pyz7/libsodium8.png?rlkey=ftf2vd6rar7nd8w4x87957u68&st=627xfjed&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the compiled program into the system. The sudo part gives administrator rights so the installation can place files in protected directories. The make install step copies the built files, such as libraries or executables, to their proper locations. After this, the software becomes available for use by all users on the system.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo ldconfig\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/8kxgxunwdkmcarln3tvit/libsodium9.png?rlkey=mac7a11cyemb1dtn2mz31w8x5&st=4lx3ly1q&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command updates the system’s shared library cache. The sudo part gives administrator rights to run it. The ldconfig tool scans the directories where libraries are stored and refreshes the list of available ones. This makes sure new libraries, like the one just installed, can be found and used by programs.\\n\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <sodium.h>\\n#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <string.h>\\n#include <stdlib.h>\\n\\nvoid print_hex(const unsigned char *data, size_t len) {\\n    for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {\\n        printf(\\\"%02x\\\", data[i]);\\n    }\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n}\\n\\nvoid demo_secret_key_encryption() {\\n    printf(\\\"=== SECRET KEY ENCRYPTION DEMO ===\\\\n\\\");\\n    const char *plaintext = \\\"This is a secret message using libsodium!\\\";\\n    size_t plaintext_len = strlen(plaintext);\\n    \\n    // Generate random key and nonce\\n    unsigned char key[crypto_secretbox_KEYBYTES];\\n    unsigned char nonce[crypto_secretbox_NONCEBYTES];\\n    \\n    crypto_secretbox_keygen(key);\\n    randombytes_buf(nonce, sizeof(nonce));\\n    \\n    // Encrypt\\n    size_t ciphertext_len = crypto_secretbox_MACBYTES + plaintext_len;\\n    unsigned char *ciphertext = malloc(ciphertext_len);\\n    \\n    if (crypto_secretbox_easy(ciphertext, (const unsigned char *)plaintext, \\n                             plaintext_len, nonce, key) != 0) {\\n        printf(\\\"Encryption failed!\\\\n\\\");\\n        free(ciphertext);\\n        return;\\n    }\\n    \\n    printf(\\\"Original message: %s\\\\n\\\", plaintext);\\n    printf(\\\"Key (%d bytes): \\\", crypto_secretbox_KEYBYTES);\\n    print_hex(key, sizeof(key));\\n    printf(\\\"Nonce (%d bytes): \\\", crypto_secretbox_NONCEBYTES);\\n    print_hex(nonce, sizeof(nonce));\\n    printf(\\\"Encrypted data (%zu bytes): \\\", ciphertext_len);\\n    print_hex(ciphertext, ciphertext_len);\\n    \\n    // Decrypt\\n    unsigned char *decrypted = malloc(plaintext_len + 1); // +1 for null terminator\\n    if (crypto_secretbox_open_easy(decrypted, ciphertext, ciphertext_len, \\n                                  nonce, key) != 0) {\\n        printf(\\\"Decryption failed!\\\\n\\\");\\n        free(ciphertext);\\n        free(decrypted);\\n        return;\\n    }\\n    \\n    // Null terminate for safe printing\\n    decrypted[plaintext_len] = \'\\\\0\';\\n    printf(\\\"Decrypted message: %s\\\\n\\\", decrypted);\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\nEncryption/Decryption successful! ✓\\\\n\\\");\\n    \\n    free(ciphertext);\\n    free(decrypted);\\n}\\n\\nint main() {\\n    // Initialize libsodium\\n    if (sodium_init() < 0) {\\n        printf(\\\"libsodium initialization failed!\\\\n\\\");\\n        return 1;\\n    }\\n    \\n    printf(\\\"libsodium Simple Crypto Demo\\\\n\\\");\\n    printf(\\\"Version: %s\\\\n\\\\n\\\", sodium_version_string());\\n    \\n    demo_secret_key_encryption();\\n    \\n    return 0;\\n}\\n\", \"explanation\": \"gcc -o crypto_demo crypto_demo.c -lsodium\\n\\nThis command compiles the crypto\\\\_demo.c program into an executable named crypto\\\\_demo. The gcc part is the compiler used for C programs. The -lsodium option links the program with the libsodium library. After running this, you can run the crypto\\\\_demo program on your system.\\n\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/wj6eybl9owgf0rlbv24jn/libsodiumTesting.png?rlkey=22iinbx6k7oxyii56io1vhvk6&st=y81cen7t&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This C program shows how to use the libsodium library for secret key encryption and decryption. It starts by initializing libsodium and printing its version. Inside the demo, it creates a random secret key and nonce, then encrypts a plaintext message using crypto\\\\_secretbox. The program prints the key, nonce, ciphertext, and finally decrypts the message back to its original form to confirm success.\\n\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(12,'lizard','Lizard','Lizard Team (Post Quantum Research)','C','2.2.0','12-12-2024','MIT',1,'https://github.com/terryyin/lizard',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','Lizard is primarily a fast compression library, not a dedicated cryptographic toolkit. While sometimes referenced in the context of data transformation, its main use is high-speed, lossless data compression for storage or transmission.','If used for security, Lizard is entirely unsuitable, as it does not provide cryptographic strength or security assurances, lacks peer review for cryptographic safety, and offers no cryptographic primitives or protocols.','[{\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/terryyin/lizard.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/vje5opkeym0d78o8qqykh/lizard0.png?rlkey=vk59kj5m5ciss34stodml1rre&st=x3578ekg&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the lizard project from GitHub to your computer. The git clone part tells Git to copy the whole repository, including files and history. The link is the address of the project on GitHub. After running this, a new folder named lizard will appear with all the project files.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"cd lizard\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/8g1xmls0vy2eolu9dnp1h/lizard1.png?rlkey=5qomxwram57z8s9htd1bp0st2&st=7e703w8f&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command changes the current working directory to the lizard folder. The cd means change directory. It moves you inside the folder that was created by the git clone command. After this, any new commands will run inside the lizard directory.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"python3 -m venv myenv\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/ycq8yoom10fyf8cf8akc4/lizard2.png?rlkey=ia4h9m2ljqb2128nkpeb585uq&st=9tshau05&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command creates a new virtual environment in Python called myenv. The python3 -m venv part tells Python to use the built-in venv module for making a separate environment. This environment keeps installed packages isolated from the system Python. The folder myenv will contain everything needed for this private setup.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"source myenv/bin/activate\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/gr998bhzspxolzrw0d88d/lizard3.png?rlkey=dqte7dx56pb0c7pc8d7aq34hh&st=d31f39hb&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command activates the Python virtual environment named myenv. The source part runs the activate script from the virtual environment folder. After activation, your shell will use the Python and packages from myenv instead of the system ones. This helps keep your project dependencies separate and organized.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"pip3 install -e .\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/nxq2f858g8bep1bqn80ao/lizard4.png?rlkey=74v3kk2surwp4jryyughpfofv&st=a728vun2&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the current project into the active Python environment in editable mode. The pip3 install part tells pip to install a package. The -e option means editable, so changes you make to the source code are used right away without reinstalling. The . refers to the current directory, which contains the project setup files.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo python3 setup.py install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/iuzvp2v8wk2vdabdbhnh5/lizard5.png?rlkey=nd3bhi6h74h772lshpja25a16&st=82gb0uye&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the Python project into the system using its setup.py file. The sudo part gives administrator rights so the installation can write to system folders. The python3 setup.py install tells Python to run the setup script, which builds and installs the package. After this, the project becomes available system-wide for all users.\\n\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#!/usr/bin/env python3\\n\\\"\\\"\\\"\\nSimple Keypair Generator\\nGenerates RSA and ECC keypairs for cryptographic operations\\n\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n\\nfrom cryptography.hazmat.primitives.asymmetric import rsa, ec\\nfrom cryptography.hazmat.primitives import serialization\\nimport argparse\\nimport sys\\n\\n\\ndef generate_rsa_keypair(key_size=2048):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Generate RSA keypair\\n    Args:\\n        key_size (int): RSA key size in bits (default: 2048)\\n    Returns:\\n        tuple: (private_key, public_key) objects\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    if key_size not in [1024, 2048, 3072, 4096]:\\n        raise ValueError(\\\"RSA key size must be 1024, 2048, 3072, or 4096 bits\\\")\\n    \\n    private_key = rsa.generate_private_key(\\n        public_exponent=65537,\\n        key_size=key_size\\n    )\\n    public_key = private_key.public_key()\\n    \\n    return private_key, public_key\\n\\n\\ndef generate_ecc_keypair(curve_name=\\\"secp256r1\\\"):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Generate ECC keypair\\n    Args:\\n        curve_name (str): Elliptic curve name (default: secp256r1)\\n    Returns:\\n        tuple: (private_key, public_key) objects\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    curve_map = {\\n        \\\"secp256r1\\\": ec.SECP256R1(),\\n        \\\"secp384r1\\\": ec.SECP384R1(),\\n        \\\"secp521r1\\\": ec.SECP521R1()\\n    }\\n    \\n    if curve_name not in curve_map:\\n        raise ValueError(f\\\"Unsupported curve: {curve_name}\\\")\\n    \\n    private_key = ec.generate_private_key(curve_map[curve_name])\\n    public_key = private_key.public_key()\\n    \\n    return private_key, public_key\\n\\n\\ndef save_private_key_pem(private_key, filename, password=None):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Save private key to PEM format file\\n    Args:\\n        private_key: Private key object\\n        filename (str): Output filename\\n        password (str): Optional password for encryption\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    if password:\\n        encryption_algorithm = serialization.BestAvailableEncryption(password.encode())\\n    else:\\n        encryption_algorithm = serialization.NoEncryption()\\n    \\n    pem = private_key.private_bytes(\\n        encoding=serialization.Encoding.PEM,\\n        format=serialization.PrivateFormat.PKCS8,\\n        encryption_algorithm=encryption_algorithm\\n    )\\n    \\n    with open(filename, \'wb\') as f:\\n        f.write(pem)\\n\\n\\ndef save_public_key_pem(public_key, filename):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Save public key to PEM format file\\n    Args:\\n        public_key: Public key object\\n        filename (str): Output filename\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    pem = public_key.public_bytes(\\n        encoding=serialization.Encoding.PEM,\\n        format=serialization.PublicFormat.SubjectPublicKeyInfo\\n    )\\n    \\n    with open(filename, \'wb\') as f:\\n        f.write(pem)\\n\\n\\ndef display_key_info(private_key, public_key, key_type):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Display information about generated keys\\n    Args:\\n        private_key: Private key object\\n        public_key: Public key object\\n        key_type (str): Type of key (RSA or ECC)\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    print(f\\\"\\\\n=== {key_type} Keypair Generated ===\\\")\\n    \\n    if key_type == \\\"RSA\\\":\\n        key_size = private_key.key_size\\n        print(f\\\"Key Size: {key_size} bits\\\")\\n    elif key_type == \\\"ECC\\\":\\n        curve_name = private_key.curve.name\\n        key_size = private_key.curve.key_size\\n        print(f\\\"Curve: {curve_name}\\\")\\n        print(f\\\"Key Size: {key_size} bits\\\")\\n    \\n    # Display key fingerprints (first 16 chars of PEM for identification)\\n    private_pem = private_key.private_bytes(\\n        encoding=serialization.Encoding.PEM,\\n        format=serialization.PrivateFormat.PKCS8,\\n        encryption_algorithm=serialization.NoEncryption()\\n    ).decode(\'utf-8\')\\n    \\n    public_pem = public_key.public_bytes(\\n        encoding=serialization.Encoding.PEM,\\n        format=serialization.PublicFormat.SubjectPublicKeyInfo\\n    ).decode(\'utf-8\')\\n    \\n    print(f\\\"Private Key Preview: {private_pem.split()[2][:16]}...\\\")\\n    print(f\\\"Public Key Preview: {public_pem.split()[2][:16]}...\\\")\\n\\n\\ndef main():\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Main function for keypair generation\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description=\\\"Generate cryptographic keypairs\\\")\\n    parser.add_argument(\\\"--type\\\", choices=[\\\"rsa\\\", \\\"ecc\\\"], default=\\\"rsa\\\", \\n                       help=\\\"Key type to generate (default: rsa)\\\")\\n    parser.add_argument(\\\"--size\\\", type=int, default=2048,\\n                       help=\\\"RSA key size in bits (default: 2048)\\\")\\n    parser.add_argument(\\\"--curve\\\", default=\\\"secp256r1\\\",\\n                       choices=[\\\"secp256r1\\\", \\\"secp384r1\\\", \\\"secp521r1\\\"],\\n                       help=\\\"ECC curve name (default: secp256r1)\\\")\\n    parser.add_argument(\\\"--save\\\", action=\\\"store_true\\\",\\n                       help=\\\"Save keys to files\\\")\\n    parser.add_argument(\\\"--prefix\\\", default=\\\"key\\\",\\n                       help=\\\"Filename prefix for saved keys (default: key)\\\")\\n    parser.add_argument(\\\"--password\\\",\\n                       help=\\\"Password to encrypt private key\\\")\\n    \\n    args = parser.parse_args()\\n    \\n    try:\\n        if args.type == \\\"rsa\\\":\\n            print(f\\\"Generating RSA keypair ({args.size} bits)...\\\")\\n            private_key, public_key = generate_rsa_keypair(args.size)\\n            display_key_info(private_key, public_key, \\\"RSA\\\")\\n            \\n            if args.save:\\n                private_filename = f\\\"{args.prefix}_private.pem\\\"\\n                public_filename = f\\\"{args.prefix}_public.pem\\\"\\n                \\n        elif args.type == \\\"ecc\\\":\\n            print(f\\\"Generating ECC keypair (curve: {args.curve})...\\\")\\n            private_key, public_key = generate_ecc_keypair(args.curve)\\n            display_key_info(private_key, public_key, \\\"ECC\\\")\\n            \\n            if args.save:\\n                private_filename = f\\\"{args.prefix}_ecc_private.pem\\\"\\n                public_filename = f\\\"{args.prefix}_ecc_public.pem\\\"\\n        \\n        # Save keys if requested\\n        if args.save:\\n            save_private_key_pem(private_key, private_filename, args.password)\\n            save_public_key_pem(public_key, public_filename)\\n            print(f\\\"\\\\nKeys saved:\\\")\\n            print(f\\\"  Private key: {private_filename}\\\")\\n            print(f\\\"  Public key: {public_filename}\\\")\\n            \\n            if args.password:\\n                print(\\\"  Private key is encrypted with password\\\")\\n    \\n    except Exception as e:\\n        print(f\\\"Error: {e}\\\")\\n        sys.exit(1)\\n\\n\\nif __name__ == \\\"__main__\\\":\\n    main()\\n\", \"explanation\": \"lizard keypair_generator.py. This command runs the Python script keypair_generator.py using the lizard framework. It executes the program to generate cryptographic keypairs as defined in the script. The script will perform the key generation and may display or save the keys depending on its code.\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/6pm2nl2cx4ieaifi7he5y/lizardtesting.png?rlkey=c9g5k7buyctbde4glsv2qmdd2&st=wia6w32a&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This Python script is a simple tool to generate RSA and ECC keypairs. It uses the cryptography library to create keys, save them in PEM format, and optionally protect private keys with a password. The program can show details such as key size, curve name, and a short preview of the keys. It also allows saving the generated keys to files if the user provides the correct options.\\n\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(13,'mbedtls','mbed TLS','ARM','C','3.6.3.1','13-05-2025','Apache 2.0',1,'https://github.com/Mbed-TLS/mbedtls',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','mbedTLS is a lightweight, portable SSL/TLS library optimized for embedded systems, IoT devices, and low-resource platforms. It offers a comprehensive suite of cryptographic primitives and protocol implementations, allowing easy integration of secure communications into constrained environments. mbedTLS is widely used in commercial and open-source embedded projects.','mbedTLS may lack some advanced features, protocol extensions, or performance optimizations found in larger SSL/TLS libraries. It is less suited for high-throughput or enterprise server environments, and may have limited hardware acceleration or compliance options for regulated industries.','[{\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/Mbed-TLS/mbedtls.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/3p1l23625b5huh3ijso8x/mbedtls0.png?rlkey=k9alkmldywy7a0w3xbrq7kzq3&st=c6yddek6&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the mbedtls project from GitHub to your computer. The git clone part tells Git to copy the full repository, including all its files and history. The link is the address of the project on GitHub. After running this, a new folder named mbedtls will appear with the project contents.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"cd mbedtls\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/vlf0ewg7mjbkrqdne5x76/mbedtls1.png?rlkey=91030hpgb5r1rw23trjly7qza&st=4a8igioj&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command changes the current working directory to the mbedtls folder. The cd means change directory. It moves you inside the folder created by the git clone command. After this, any commands you run will work inside the mbedtls directory.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"git submodule update --init --recursive\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/wabfvlido7x00nkrve9dk/mbedtls2.png?rlkey=z652t1qg42iyztsd7kzrlq4p6&st=nfdvar5y&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads and updates all submodules used in the project. The git submodule update part makes sure submodules are ready. The --init option initializes them if they are not set up yet. The --recursive option makes sure even nested submodules are updated fully.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"mkdir build && cd build\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/w3fcwo6a32lcijkg2dpkz/mbedtls3.png?rlkey=2i77eculplbqynerf0h2il4xh&st=4sevrocm&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command creates a new folder named build and then moves into it. The mkdir build part makes the directory if it does not exist. The && means the next command runs only if the first one is successful. The cd build then changes the current working directory to the new build folder.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"cmake -DENABLE_PROGRAMS=ON -DENABLE_TESTING=OFF -DUSE_SHARED_MBEDTLS_LIBRARY=ON .. \", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/hncfo4dypu5bjy4npcoi7/mbedtls4.png?rlkey=t76yi5gzvish1robeeqww9v50&st=8wush138&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command runs cmake to configure how the mbedtls project will be built. The option -DENABLE\\\\_PROGRAMS=ON tells it to build example programs. The option -DENABLE\\\\_TESTING=OFF disables building test files. The option -DUSE\\\\_SHARED\\\\_MBEDTLS\\\\_LIBRARY=ON makes it build shared libraries instead of static ones, and the .. points to the source folder above the build directory.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/l56fgeb7kuy4cgsce1hv1/mbedtls5.png?rlkey=6zwonkdex6d83ghpukyzkecco&st=txj72nwo&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the mbedtls project based on the configuration set by cmake. The make tool reads the build instructions created earlier. It then uses the compiler to build the source code into programs and libraries. After this step, the compiled files will be ready inside the build folder.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/u6iuj86mz6ozfwrydfw8q/mbedtls6.png?rlkey=x5enbv74p4uxum7rxt1gh3lkd&st=4rb4q0rw&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the compiled mbedtls files into the system. The sudo part gives administrator rights so files can be copied into system directories. The make install step places the libraries, headers, and tools in their correct locations. After this, mbedtls is available for use by all programs on the system.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo ldconfig\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/uamy166f09gopgi5bab2a/mbedtls7.png?rlkey=ue5i6z69z154roaf1idr6f5do&st=amkpc86e&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command refreshes the system’s shared library cache. The sudo part gives administrator rights to run it. The ldconfig tool scans the library folders and updates the list of available libraries. This makes sure newly installed libraries, like mbedtls, can be found and used by applications.\\n\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <string.h>\\n#include <mbedtls/aes.h>\\n\\n#define BLOCK_SIZE 16  // AES block size is 16 bytes\\n\\nvoid print_hex(const char* label, const unsigned char* data, size_t len) {\\n    printf(\\\"%s: \\\", label);\\n    for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {\\n        printf(\\\"%02x\\\", data[i]);\\n    }\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n}\\n\\nint main() {\\n    // Initialize variables\\n    mbedtls_aes_context aes;\\n    unsigned char key[32] = \\\"MySecretKey123456789012345678901\\\";  // 256-bit key\\n    unsigned char plaintext[BLOCK_SIZE] = \\\"Hello Mbed TLS!\\\";     // 16 bytes (padded with \\\\0)\\n    unsigned char ciphertext[BLOCK_SIZE];\\n    unsigned char decrypted[BLOCK_SIZE];\\n    int ret;\\n\\n    printf(\\\"=== Mbed TLS AES Encryption Demo ===\\\\n\\\\n\\\");\\n\\n    // Initialize AES context\\n    mbedtls_aes_init(&aes);\\n\\n    // Set encryption key\\n    ret = mbedtls_aes_setkey_enc(&aes, key, 256);\\n    if (ret != 0) {\\n        printf(\\\"Error: Failed to set encryption key (-%04x)\\\\n\\\", -ret);\\n        goto cleanup;\\n    }\\n\\n    // Display original data\\n    printf(\\\"Original message: %s\\\\n\\\", plaintext);\\n    print_hex(\\\"Plaintext (hex)\\\", plaintext, BLOCK_SIZE);\\n    print_hex(\\\"Key (hex)\\\", key, 32);\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n\\n    // Encrypt the data (1 = encrypt mode)\\n    ret = mbedtls_aes_crypt_ecb(&aes, 1, plaintext, ciphertext);\\n    if (ret != 0) {\\n        printf(\\\"Error: Encryption failed (-%04x)\\\\n\\\", -ret);\\n        goto cleanup;\\n    }\\n\\n    print_hex(\\\"Encrypted (hex)\\\", ciphertext, BLOCK_SIZE);\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n\\n    // Set decryption key\\n    ret = mbedtls_aes_setkey_dec(&aes, key, 256);\\n    if (ret != 0) {\\n        printf(\\\"Error: Failed to set decryption key (-%04x)\\\\n\\\", -ret);\\n        goto cleanup;\\n    }\\n\\n    // Decrypt the data (0 = decrypt mode)\\n    ret = mbedtls_aes_crypt_ecb(&aes, 0, ciphertext, decrypted);\\n    if (ret != 0) {\\n        printf(\\\"Error: Decryption failed (-%04x)\\\\n\\\", -ret);\\n        goto cleanup;\\n    }\\n\\n    // Display results\\n    print_hex(\\\"Decrypted (hex)\\\", decrypted, BLOCK_SIZE);\\n    printf(\\\"Decrypted message: %s\\\\n\\\", decrypted);\\n\\n    // Verify the decryption worked\\n    if (memcmp(plaintext, decrypted, BLOCK_SIZE) == 0) {\\n        printf(\\\"\\\\n✓ SUCCESS: Decryption matches original!\\\\n\\\");\\n    } else {\\n        printf(\\\"\\\\n✗ ERROR: Decryption doesn\'t match original!\\\\n\\\");\\n    }\\n\\ncleanup:\\n    // Clean up\\n    mbedtls_aes_free(&aes);\\n    return ret;\\n}\", \"explanation\": \"[Compile command: gcc -o aes_demo aes_demo.c -I/usr/local/include -ltfpsacrypto\\nexport LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/usr/local/lib:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH ]\\n\\nThe first command compiles the aes\\\\_demo.c program into an executable named aes\\\\_demo. The -I/usr/local/include option tells the compiler where to find header files, and -ltfpsacrypto links the program with the tfpsacrypto library.\\n\\nThe second command updates the system’s library path so the program can find shared libraries in /usr/local/lib.\\n\\nThe third command runs the compiled aes\\\\_demo program, which will perform the AES encryption and decryption defined in the code.\\n\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/nsxzs2o5opb21wl1kofk7/mbestesting.png?rlkey=klfxgzqoau2dnrv6xf1pd5hdz&st=ik02k95p&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This C program shows how to use Mbed TLS for AES encryption and decryption in ECB mode. It sets up a 256-bit secret key and encrypts a 16-byte plaintext message. The program then decrypts the ciphertext back to the original message. Finally, it prints the key, plaintext, ciphertext, and decrypted data in both text and hexadecimal form, and checks if the decryption is correct.\\n\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(14,'mpspdz','Mpspdz','Marcel Keller','Python, C++','0.3.3','20-11-2024','MIT',1,'https://github.com/data61/MP-SPDZ',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','MPSPDZ is a state-of-the-art framework for secure multi-party computation (MPC), supporting a range of protocols that allow parties to compute joint functions over their private data without revealing the data itself. It is widely used in academic and experimental research settings for privacy-preserving computation, benchmarking, and protocol development.','MPSPDZ is complex to set up and operate, requires deep cryptographic knowledge, and is not designed for production deployment or non-expert users. It is resource-intensive and may lack the performance, stability, and support required for commercial applications.','[{\"command\": \"sudo apt-get update\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/fplcqcknfuby5coaumve3/mpspdz0.png?rlkey=yduqfph2giugtxd5zk9ph1q98&st=y5aj2hjq&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command updates the package list on your Linux system. The sudo part gives administrator rights to run it. The apt-get update step contacts the software repositories and downloads the latest information about available packages. This makes sure your system knows about the newest versions before installing or upgrading software.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo apt-get install -y automake build-essential clang cmake git libboost-dev libboost-filesystem-dev libboost-iostreams-dev libboost-thread-dev libgmp-dev libntl-dev libsodium-dev libssl-dev libtool python3\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/c7umpogztwl4iw59fb8ve/mpspdz1.png?rlkey=q7omlid8ecahnme6c807tenx7&st=yv1u46f7&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs many development tools and libraries needed for building software. The sudo part gives administrator rights, and apt-get install tells the system to download and set them up. The -y option means it will install without asking for confirmation. The listed packages include compilers, build tools, Boost libraries, GMP, NTL, libsodium, OpenSSL, libtool, and Python 3, which are often required for cryptography and software development.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/data61/MP-SPDZ.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/85j2ciknrnzcb4d5mnig3/mpspdz2.png?rlkey=r8wibclgxz276sjqtixbv4ksu&st=cukkc4vx&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the MP-SPDZ project from GitHub to your computer. The git clone part tells Git to copy the full repository with all files and history. The link is the address of the project on GitHub. After running this, a new folder named MP-SPDZ will appear with the project files.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"cd MP-SPDZ\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/e39amn2jjtdq0wjn3ljzs/mpspdz3.png?rlkey=w3359wzbvuaju0blxzsumid0l&st=ioej51tw&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command changes the current working directory to the MP-SPDZ folder. The cd means change directory. It moves you inside the folder that was created by the git clone command. After this, any commands you run will work inside the MP-SPDZ directory.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"make -j$(nproc)\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/p1uke3s1di9kwrkt0v1n4/mpspdz4.png?rlkey=js3yjsegayyvgihgal6pdcbvz&st=1xa49z3l&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the MP-SPDZ project using all available processor cores. The make part starts the build process. The -j option allows multiple compilation jobs to run at the same time. The \\\\$(nproc) part gets the number of CPU cores, so the build is faster by using them all.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"make setup\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/pji07k2ujz6zjhfw72jo9/mpspdz5.png?rlkey=ql6bnnuv21wdmchh73zic45n6&st=u1x2dbva&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command prepares the MP-SPDZ project for use after it has been compiled. The make setup step runs setup tasks defined in the project’s makefile. It usually creates necessary folders, copies files, or downloads extra data needed to run the system. This ensures the environment is ready before running the software.\\n\"}]','[{\"command\": \"from Compiler.library import *\\n\\ndef main():\\n    print_ln(\\\"=== Simple Cryptography Demo (Modular Addition, mod 256) ===\\\")\\n\\n    # Party 0 input\\n    a = sint.get_input_from(0)\\n\\n    # Party 1 input\\n    b = sint.get_input_from(1)\\n\\n    # Modulus must be power of two (here 256 = 2^8)\\n    c = (a + b) % (1 << 8)\\n\\n    # Reveal result\\n    print_ln(\\\"Result (a + b mod 256): %s\\\", c.reveal())\\n\\nmain()\", \"explanation\": \"[Compile command: echo 200 > Player-Data/Input-P0-0\\necho 100 > Player-Data/Input-P1-0\\nScripts/compile-run.py -E semi simple_modadd] The first two commands write the numbers 200 and 100 into input files for Party 0 and Party 1. The third command runs the MP-SPDZ script compile-run.py to execute a secure computation. It uses semi-honest mode (-E semi) and runs the simple modular addition program. The result will be computed securely and revealed according to the program.\\n\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/z1xa5erxvrvbs5uw5zm8q/mpspdztesting.png?rlkey=ao0skvy45dsq2bvqwhipnakqq&st=9mzhaj3k&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This Python program is written for the MP-SPDZ framework to demonstrate simple secure computation. It imports functions from Compiler.library and defines a main function. Party 0 provides the first secret input, and Party 1 provides the second secret input. The program adds the two numbers, takes the result modulo 256, and then securely reveals the final result to all parties.\\n\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(15,'nettle','Nettle','Nettle Team Project','C, Assembly','4.1','22-03-2025','LGPLv3 / GPLv2',1,'https://github.com/gnutls/nettle',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','Nettle is a low-level cryptographic library intended as a building block for higher-level libraries and applications. It provides a wide range of cryptographic primitives but leaves protocol implementation to developers. Its modularity makes it suitable for integration into projects requiring custom cryptographic solutions.','Nettle does not provide protocol-level abstractions or utilities, increasing the risk of misuse by non-experts. Developers must take care to properly combine primitives to avoid introducing vulnerabilities.','[{\"command\": \"sudo apt install build-essential autotools-dev automake libtool libgmp-dev texinfo\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/zwdq2urzt43zmj0ojdxgo/nettle0.png?rlkey=63og6osqr59ozepuima9gtmhf&st=hhhm8n67&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs important tools and libraries for building software from source. The sudo part gives administrator rights, and apt install downloads and sets them up. The packages include compilers, GNU build tools (autotools, automake, libtool), the GMP library for big numbers, and texinfo for documentation. These are often required when compiling cryptographic or mathematical libraries.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/gnutls/nettle.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/xvqovkygtdy7kgxjealu3/nettle1.png?rlkey=n8ge9oj6yryk5a04u5gvfw5ke&st=hc0pt746&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the nettle project from GitHub to your computer. The git clone part tells Git to copy the whole repository, including files and history. The link is the address of the project on GitHub. After running this, a new folder named nettle will appear with the project files.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"cd nettle\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/hb1e5av0s67djq8qrahww/nettle2.png?rlkey=ow2v0f9yzt7voxt45bs2jlyus&st=qqiuc3lc&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command changes the current working directory to the nettle folder. The cd means change directory. It moves you inside the folder that was created by the git clone command. After this, any commands you run will work inside the nettle directory.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"./.bootstrap\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/ial1y6hz8guk5aeqntl7y/nettle3.png?rlkey=13u8s4269i2ofmbe3o8tf3wms&st=ww2jspko&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command runs the .bootstrap script in the nettle folder. The ./ tells the system to execute a file from the current directory. The script usually prepares the build system by generating configuration files and setting up autotools. It is a required step before running configure and make.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"./configure --prefix=/usr --disable-static\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/aksom91dk6o03efzf2e91/nettle4.png?rlkey=6mmcuo8kfx5iljno1ihzbb2kn&st=srpxm9bq&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command runs the configure script to prepare the build settings for nettle. The --prefix=/usr option tells it to install the library under /usr instead of the default /usr/local. The --disable-static option disables building static libraries, so only shared libraries will be created. This step sets up makefiles that will be used in the compilation process.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/fl8ej1qozqiimq3bjxk9w/nettle5.png?rlkey=dniuk6rtxtaiuarife7ynmrsh&st=dez4nain&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the nettle project based on the settings from configure. The make tool reads the makefile and builds the source code into libraries and programs. It uses the compiler and other tools to generate the required files. After this step, the compiled files are ready but not yet installed system-wide.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/zigxkuibmf3gx5h9qmuix/nettle6.png?rlkey=amlmslcplvmvrsd20ck7gdbyq&st=pk5uo5pm&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the compiled nettle files into the system. The sudo part gives administrator rights so the files can be copied into protected directories. The make install step places the libraries, headers, and tools in their correct locations. After this, nettle is available for use by all users and applications on the system.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo ldconfig\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/veyv467fpw345phwu1yks/nettle7.png?rlkey=tkr6fq15105iyu7uttyine2qf&st=0btmm8gd&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command updates the system’s shared library cache. The sudo part gives administrator rights to run it. The ldconfig tool scans library directories and refreshes the list of available libraries. This makes sure newly installed libraries like nettle can be found and used by programs.\\n\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <string.h>\\n#include <nettle/sha2.h>\\n\\nint main() {\\n    printf(\\\"=== Simple SHA-256 Hash with Nettle ===\\\\n\\\\n\\\");\\n    \\n    // Message to hash\\n    const char* message = \\\"Hello, Nettle!\\\";\\n    printf(\\\"Message: %s\\\\n\\\", message);\\n    printf(\\\"Length: %zu bytes\\\\n\\\\n\\\", strlen(message));\\n    \\n    // Create SHA-256 context\\n    struct sha256_ctx ctx;\\n    \\n    // Initialize the hash context\\n    sha256_init(&ctx);\\n    \\n    // Update with our message\\n    sha256_update(&ctx, strlen(message), (const uint8_t*)message);\\n    \\n    // Buffer to store the hash (SHA-256 = 32 bytes)\\n    uint8_t hash[32];\\n    \\n    // Finalize and get the hash\\n    sha256_digest(&ctx, sizeof(hash), hash);\\n    \\n    // Print the hash in hexadecimal\\n    printf(\\\"SHA-256 Hash: \\\");\\n    for (int i = 0; i < 32; i++) {\\n        printf(\\\"%02x\\\", hash[i]);\\n    }\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n    \\n    return 0;\\n}\", \"explanation\": \"[Compile Command: gcc hash_demo.c -o hash_demo -lnettle] This command compiles the hash\\\\_demo.c program into an executable named hash\\\\_demo. The gcc part is the C compiler used to build the program. The -lnettle option links the program with the Nettle library for cryptographic functions. After running this, you can run hash\\\\_demo to compute hashes using Nettle.\\n\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/3dd1rliwstylk87jdlzpe/nettletesting.png?rlkey=amwg2909g64m6iccmeup06ct3&st=39s9sm50&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This C program shows how to compute a SHA-256 hash using the Nettle library. It starts by defining a message and initializing a SHA-256 context. The program updates the context with the message, then finalizes the hash into a 32-byte buffer. Finally, it prints the original message and the resulting hash in hexadecimal form.\\n\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(16,'networksecurityservices','Network Security Services(NSS)\n','Mozilla','C','3.9','12-02-2023','MPL/GPL/LGPL',1,'https://github.com/nss-dev/nss',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','Network Security Services (NSS) is a comprehensive set of libraries for developing security-enabled client and server applications, supporting SSL, TLS, S/MIME, and PKI. Widely used in Mozilla products and enterprise software, NSS is known for its cross-platform support, rich feature set, and robust implementation of security protocols.','NSS’s complexity, large codebase, and intricate configuration can present integration challenges, especially for smaller projects or new developers. Its API is less intuitive than some modern alternatives, and documentation, while extensive, may be difficult to navigate.','[{\"command\": \"sudo apt install -y build-essential git mercurial libnspr4-dev zlib1g-dev libsqlite3-dev gyp ninja-build pkg-config\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/jskotgr4n97cbhbbz7bcj/nss0.png?rlkey=4g9lc402jtt13hzrgeo9edswm&st=1x36oqho&raw=1\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/nss-dev/nss.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/rg1euf3hgyl0qso6wv95p/nss1.png?rlkey=l75y1q650yehsvlwj7wvyk94u&st=tvrhuh40&raw=1\"}, {\"command\": \"cd nss\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/9r0x74vzdo3dnwq379itz/nss3.png?rlkey=yracodnnfb2ers8gfqnz4td03&st=kfuoftfz&raw=1\"}, {\"command\": \"hg clone https://hg.mozilla.org/projects/nspr\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/1zaug066ljd44ykg73u49/nss2.png?rlkey=oltytgy8jmb61ml7hpee4fs5q&st=173vy9ln&raw=1\"}, {\"command\": \"export BUILD_OPT=1\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/y6n1ywj5kic9of4j868fk/nss4.png?rlkey=oipnjwabx8s0zsxcg94e2kzf8&st=n7sjcpvc&raw=1\"}, {\"command\": \"export USE_64=1 \", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/olram5b55rm7aojpwepdu/nss5.png?rlkey=qdgknnwynlg9tihuiwzijw476&st=t4nvil2k&raw=1\"}, {\"command\": \"make nss_build_all\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/ra3j0738569zr154dum9g/nss6.png?rlkey=qsbynja3oqyw7wlr7fsnxs4fc&st=uwjbk1z4&raw=1\"}, {\"command\": \"export NSS_HOME=~/nss-workspace/dist/Release\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/mb8iennn0dx0yxz77y1dv/nss7.png?rlkey=1wxg936y9e07abtau0zbltxfi&st=z26befll&raw=1\"}, {\"command\": \"export PATH=$NSS_HOME/bin:$PATH\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/afc3imhrzh22wuu29p7ym/nss8.png?rlkey=a8cu87hdvh04x4hyud0tt5rde&st=lknjl5y5&raw=1\"}, {\"command\": \"export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=$NSS_HOME/lib:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/dwq5fehovwe7fjoe32hcb/nss9.png?rlkey=c3fdqk67evg8n9067ev0ts6gh&st=45ihhf1j&raw=1\"}, {\"command\": \"export PKG_CONFIG_PATH=$NSS_HOME/lib/pkgconfig:$PKG_CONFIG_PATH\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/x280nacr2vpxrnfj71o92/nss10.png?rlkey=qxsl9pgfrayietwtize203xg2&st=vcamtprb&raw=1\"}, {\"command\": \"source ~/.bashrc\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/1uuzdbpol053lo0ir2xm2/nss11.png?rlkey=93scyt5gmxuub8nai8545gs5q&st=8xvsot4g&raw=1\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <stdlib.h>\\n#include <string.h>\\n#include <nss.h>\\n#include <pk11pub.h>\\n#include <sechash.h>\\n\\nvoid print_hex(const unsigned char *data, size_t len) {\\n   for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {\\n       printf(\\\"%02x\\\", data[i]);\\n   }\\n   printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n}\\n\\nint sha256_hash(const char *input, unsigned char *output) {\\n   SECStatus rv;\\n   PK11Context *context;\\n   unsigned int output_len;\\n  \\n   // Create a digest context for SHA-256\\n   context = PK11_CreateDigestContext(SEC_OID_SHA256);\\n   if (!context) {\\n       fprintf(stderr, \\\"Failed to create digest context\\\\n\\\");\\n       return -1;\\n   }\\n  \\n   // Initialize the digest operation\\n   rv = PK11_DigestBegin(context);\\n   if (rv != SECSuccess) {\\n       fprintf(stderr, \\\"Failed to begin digest operation\\\\n\\\");\\n       PK11_DestroyContext(context, PR_TRUE);\\n       return -1;\\n   }\\n  \\n   // Update the digest with input data\\n   rv = PK11_DigestOp(context, (unsigned char*)input, strlen(input));\\n   if (rv != SECSuccess) {\\n       fprintf(stderr, \\\"Failed to update digest\\\\n\\\");\\n       PK11_DestroyContext(context, PR_TRUE);\\n       return -1;\\n   }\\n  \\n   // Finalize the digest and get the result\\n   rv = PK11_DigestFinal(context, output, &output_len, SHA256_LENGTH);\\n   if (rv != SECSuccess) {\\n       fprintf(stderr, \\\"Failed to finalize digest\\\\n\\\");\\n       PK11_DestroyContext(context, PR_TRUE);\\n       return -1;\\n   }\\n  \\n   // Clean up\\n   PK11_DestroyContext(context, PR_TRUE);\\n  \\n   return output_len;\\n}\\n\\nint main(int argc, char *argv[]) {\\n   SECStatus rv;\\n   unsigned char hash[SHA256_LENGTH];\\n   const char *input;\\n  \\n   // Check command line arguments\\n   if (argc != 2) {\\n       printf(\\\"Usage: %s <string_to_hash>\\\\n\\\", argv[0]);\\n       printf(\\\"Example: %s \\\\\\\"Hello, World!\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\", argv[0]);\\n       return 1;\\n   }\\n  \\n   input = argv[1];\\n  \\n   // Initialize NSS\\n   rv = NSS_NoDB_Init(NULL);\\n   if (rv != SECSuccess) {\\n       fprintf(stderr, \\\"Failed to initialize NSS\\\\n\\\");\\n       return 1;\\n   }\\n  \\n   printf(\\\"NSS Crypto Library - SHA-256 Hash Example\\\\n\\\");\\n   printf(\\\"=========================================\\\\n\\\");\\n   printf(\\\"Input string: \\\\\\\"%s\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\", input);\\n   printf(\\\"Input length: %zu bytes\\\\n\\\", strlen(input));\\n   printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n  \\n   // Calculate SHA-256 hash\\n   int hash_len = sha256_hash(input, hash);\\n   if (hash_len < 0) {\\n       fprintf(stderr, \\\"Failed to calculate hash\\\\n\\\");\\n       NSS_Shutdown();\\n       return 1;\\n   }\\n  \\n   // Display results\\n   printf(\\\"SHA-256 Hash:\\\\n\\\");\\n   printf(\\\"Hex: \\\");\\n   print_hex(hash, hash_len);\\n   printf(\\\"Length: %d bytes\\\\n\\\", hash_len);\\n  \\n   // Additional examples with predefined strings\\n   printf(\\\"\\\\n--- Additional Examples ---\\\\n\\\");\\n  \\n   const char *test_strings[] = {\\n       \\\"hello\\\",\\n       \\\"NSS Crypto Library\\\",\\n       \\\"The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog\\\",\\n       \\\"\\\"\\n   };\\n  \\n   int num_tests = sizeof(test_strings) / sizeof(test_strings[0]);\\n  \\n   for (int i = 0; i < num_tests; i++) {\\n       int len = sha256_hash(test_strings[i], hash);\\n       if (len > 0) {\\n           printf(\\\"Input: \\\\\\\"%s\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\", test_strings[i]);\\n           printf(\\\"SHA-256: \\\");\\n           print_hex(hash, len);\\n           printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n       }\\n   }\\n  \\n   // Cleanup NSS\\n   NSS_Shutdown();\\n  \\n   return 0;\\n}\", \"explanation\": \"Compile command: gcc demo_sha256.c \\\\\\n  -I./dist/public/nss \\\\\\n  -I./dist/Linux6.14_x86_64_cc_glibc_PTH_64_OPT.OBJ/include \\\\\\n  -L./dist/Linux6.14_x86_64_cc_glibc_PTH_64_OPT.OBJ/lib \\\\\\n  -lnss3 -lnssutil3 -lsmime3 -lssl3 -lnspr4 -lplc4 -lplds4 ] This command compiles the demo\\\\_sha256.c program into an executable using the gcc compiler. The -I options tell the compiler where to find the header files for NSS and system libraries. The -L option specifies the folder where the linker can find the library files. The -l options link the program with NSS, SSL, and NSPR libraries needed for cryptographic functions.\\n\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/wi920k873ccpc07f7y3x8/nsstesting.png?rlkey=2ffbohfd6n3n894ln0l8pp3oq&st=avtnqvv9&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(17,'pqclean','PQClean','Community','C','0.3','17-04-2023','MIT',1,'https://github.com/PQClean/PQClean',1,'\"Kyber, Dilithium, Falcon\"','PQClean offers clean, portable C implementations of post-quantum cryptographic algorithms, serving as a reference for researchers, cryptographic competitions, and developers wanting to integrate quantum-safe algorithms into other libraries.','PQClean prioritizes correctness and clarity over speed and production readiness, lacking extensive optimization, hardening, and long-term support. It is not recommended for direct use in production systems without additional review and adaptation.','[{\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/PQClean/PQClean.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/g00nkz5khh5iwhlgsu1dt/1.png?rlkey=1mt76d3ggne4glxs0j11tow44&st=t5u8ei84&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The command `git clone https://github.com/PQClean/PQClean.git` makes a copy of the PQClean project from GitHub to your computer. It downloads all the files and folders in that project. After running this, you will have a local folder named `PQClean` with the same content as the online repository.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd PQClean\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/dz1a7ttl162audzelcwyz/2.png?rlkey=3u1pntt68rz3uyjc8cljn8yyk&st=tdw2p5n3&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The command `cd PQClean` means \\\"change directory to PQClean.\\\" It moves you into the PQClean folder so you can work with the files inside it.\"}, {\"command\": \"python3 -m venv venv\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/kejwukgrtsk09k36yu2we/3.png?rlkey=s84jza1o4yrn50uasldgpu31c&st=fsmwfdyj&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The command `python3 -m venv venv` creates a virtual environment named `venv`. A virtual environment is like a separate space to install Python packages without affecting the whole system. This helps keep your project’s tools and libraries organized.\"}, {\"command\": \"source venv/bin/activate\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/zxqs9ek43ifryi8hsnhea/4.png?rlkey=bttuhrk13sr8yxshbyqm3vwkz&st=e6m9b1fi&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The command `source venv/bin/activate` turns on the virtual environment you created. After this, any Python packages you install or run will stay inside the `venv` folder, not your whole system. This helps avoid conflicts between projects.\"}, {\"command\": \"pip install -r requirements.txt\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/6jngsjz1npz7mfxgax6gs/5.png?rlkey=rs6q6fud90id0ncde9lz9zyr6&st=ljh99e38&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The command `pip install -r requirements.txt` installs all the Python packages listed in the `requirements.txt` file. These packages are needed for the project to work properly. It makes sure your environment has the same tools the project needs.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <stdint.h>\\n#include <stdlib.h>\\n#include \\\"api.h\\\"\\n\\n// Inline randombytes implementation\\nvoid PQCLEAN_randombytes(uint8_t *buf, size_t n) {\\n    FILE *fp = fopen(\\\"/dev/urandom\\\", \\\"rb\\\");\\n    if (!fp) {\\n        fprintf(stderr, \\\"Cannot open /dev/urandom\\\\n\\\");\\n        exit(1);\\n    }\\n    if (fread(buf, 1, n, fp) != n) {\\n        fprintf(stderr, \\\"Failed to read random bytes\\\\n\\\");\\n        fclose(fp);\\n        exit(1);\\n    }\\n    fclose(fp);\\n}\\n\\nint main(void) {\\n    uint8_t pk[PQCLEAN_FALCON512_CLEAN_CRYPTO_PUBLICKEYBYTES];\\n    uint8_t sk[PQCLEAN_FALCON512_CLEAN_CRYPTO_SECRETKEYBYTES];\\n\\n    if (PQCLEAN_FALCON512_CLEAN_crypto_sign_keypair(pk, sk) != 0) {\\n        fprintf(stderr, \\\"Keypair generation failed!\\\\n\\\");\\n        return 1;\\n    }\\n\\n    printf(\\\"Public Key:\\\\n\\\");\\n    for (size_t i = 0; i < sizeof(pk); i++) {\\n        printf(\\\"%02x\\\", pk[i]);\\n        if ((i+1) % 32 == 0) printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n    }\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\\nSecret Key:\\\\n\\\");\\n    for (size_t i = 0; i < sizeof(sk); i++) {\\n        printf(\\\"%02x\\\", sk[i]);\\n        if ((i+1) % 32 == 0) printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n    }\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\n    return 0;\\n}\", \"explanation\": \"In the `PQClean/crypto_sign/falcon-512/clean` directory, copy the required files using the commands `cp /home/user/Desktop/PQClean/common/fips202.* .` and `cp /home/user/Desktop/PQClean/common/sha2.* .`, ensuring that the directory paths are correct. Then, compile the copied files using `gcc -c fips202.c` and `gcc -c sha2.c`. Next, create a new file named `falcon_keygen.c` and insert the provided code into it. After that, compile the program using the command `gcc falcon_keygen.c common.o fpr.o fft.o keygen.o codec.o sign.o vrfy.o fips202.o sha2.o rng.o pqclean.o -o falcon_keygen`, and finally, run the program.\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/s8oynwn9jp1ml5sivuuie/pqclean_testing.png?rlkey=a66448jm536yjqsnhcann8yef&st=1cbw2v3j&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The image shown above displays the output generated from the keypair generation process. In this process, a pair of cryptographic keys is created: a public key, which can be shared openly, and a secret key, which must be kept private. These keys are essential components in secure communication and digital signature operations, especially in post-quantum cryptographic algorithms such as Falcon. The output confirms that the keypair was successfully generated and is ready to be used in further cryptographic tasks like signing or verifying data.\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(18,'themis','Themis','Cossack Labs','C/C++/Go/Java','0.15.6','10-01-2026','Apache 2.0',1,'https://github.com/cossacklabs/themis',1,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','Themis is an open-source cryptographic library providing high-level APIs for secure messaging, data storage, authentication, and transport layer security. It is designed to be easy to use, with clear documentation and support for multiple programming languages, making it suitable for mobile, web, and backend applications.','Themis does not cover all cryptographic protocols or advanced standards, and may not offer sufficient flexibility for specialized or regulated environments needing fine-grained cryptographic control or compliance features.','[{\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/cossacklabs/themis.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/how0q1ujhmtrgh81yq8in/themis0.png?rlkey=o9fttpb7ffmexvhh116915nkp&st=m0gyc58l&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the themis project from GitHub to your computer. The git clone part tells Git to copy the entire repository with all its files and history. The link is the address of the project on GitHub. After running this, a new folder named themis will appear with the project contents.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"cd themis\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/wmz10np5pkk6nx1ar4m70/themis1.png?rlkey=j6834fwvwsrmklop4cjah9use&st=dm3c2h0t&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"That command moves you into the **themis** directory you just cloned, so now you’ll be inside the project’s folder and can build or run setup commands from there.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/2uerbreova4lat3016i58/themis2.png?rlkey=3b6l80g48qqglulmlojpq5p04&st=hyvz2qjr&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the themis project using the instructions in the Makefile. It reads the rules and builds the source code into executable programs and libraries. The compiler and other tools are used to generate the final files. After this, the software is ready to be installed or used.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/apdgp3b2wi4ju4wik7ath/themis3.png?rlkey=6uvr5rwuhywoy9rjcli6v7mcs&st=z2sxfvcp&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the compiled themis files into the system. The sudo part gives administrator rights so the files can be copied into protected directories. The make install step places the libraries, headers, and programs in their correct locations. After this, themis can be used by all users and applications on the system.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo ldconfig\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/5jxoapuvx50s1atxbvdpg/themis4.png?rlkey=miqy9xqso5ppyhxl7m3mwakz6&st=2bwm7btz&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command updates the system’s shared library cache. The sudo part gives administrator rights to run it. The ldconfig tool scans library directories and refreshes the list of available libraries. This ensures that newly installed libraries like themis can be found and used by programs.\\n\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <themis/themis.h>\\n#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <stdlib.h>\\n\\nvoid print_hex(const char* name, const uint8_t* data, size_t len) {\\n   printf(\\\"%s (%zu bytes):\\\\n\\\", name, len);\\n   for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) printf(\\\"%02x\\\", data[i]);\\n   printf(\\\"\\\\n\\\\n\\\");\\n}\\n\\nint main() {\\n   size_t priv_len=0, pub_len=0;\\n\\n   // EC\\n   themis_gen_ec_key_pair(NULL,&priv_len,NULL,&pub_len);\\n   uint8_t* ec_priv=malloc(priv_len),*ec_pub=malloc(pub_len);\\n   themis_gen_ec_key_pair(ec_priv,&priv_len,ec_pub,&pub_len);\\n   print_hex(\\\"EC Private Key\\\", ec_priv, priv_len);\\n   print_hex(\\\"EC Public Key\\\", ec_pub, pub_len);\\n   free(ec_priv); free(ec_pub);\\n\\n   // RSA\\n   priv_len=pub_len=0;\\n   themis_gen_rsa_key_pair(NULL,&priv_len,NULL,&pub_len);\\n   uint8_t* rsa_priv=malloc(priv_len),*rsa_pub=malloc(pub_len);\\n   themis_gen_rsa_key_pair(rsa_priv,&priv_len,rsa_pub,&pub_len);\\n   print_hex(\\\"RSA Private Key\\\", rsa_priv, priv_len);\\n   print_hex(\\\"RSA Public Key\\\", rsa_pub, pub_len);\\n   free(rsa_priv); free(rsa_pub);\\n\\n   // Symmetric\\n   //uint8_t sym[32];\\n   //themis_secure_random(sym, sizeof(sym));\\n   //print_hex(\\\"Symmetric Key\\\", sym, sizeof(sym));\\n\\n   return 0;\\n}\", \"explanation\": \"[Compile command: gcc -o keygen keygen.c $(pkg-config --cflags --libs libthemis)] This command compiles the keygen.c program into an executable named keygen. The gcc part is the C compiler. The \\\\$(pkg-config --cflags --libs libthemis) part adds the correct compiler flags and links the program with the Themis library. After running this, you can run keygen to generate cryptographic keys using Themis.\\n\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/16zwqshxmb6fa93s2ut47/themistest.png?rlkey=8zrck3e1jizreq8lf5566obr8&st=3gtzk0rf&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This C program demonstrates key generation using the Themis library. It first generates an elliptic curve (EC) keypair and prints the private and public keys in hexadecimal. Then it generates an RSA keypair and prints those keys as well. The program shows how to allocate memory, generate keys, and display them safely.\\n\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(19,'wolfcrypt','wolfCrypt','wolfSSL','C','5.8.0','24-04-2025','GPL v2',1,'https://github.com/wolfSSL/wolfEngine',1,'\"Kyber, Dilithium, SPHINCS+, LMS, XMSS\"','wolfCrypt is the cryptographic engine of wolfSSL, specifically engineered for embedded, IoT, and resource-constrained platforms. It supports a wide array of algorithms, FIPS certification, and hardware acceleration, and is praised for its portability, performance, and robust commercial support.','wolfCrypt’s focus on lightweight and portable cryptography means it may lack support for some advanced, experimental, or less commonly used algorithms and protocols. It may not be the best fit for large-scale server environments requiring broad protocol coverage or enterprise-grade features.','[{\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/wolfSSL/wolfssl.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/gh8vqrzzhexb0ka34kpkt/wolfcrypt0.png?rlkey=nwhhii2371vccb5yvoocyt2h2&st=v2wg0b9o&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the wolfssl project from GitHub. It creates a folder with all the project files.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd wolfssl\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/d5zj37v0yf472q4n30g5f/wolfcrypt1.png?rlkey=fy7cth1vyhy903w6eqhwsfpy8&st=b8bqo8jn&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves you into the wolfssl folder. You can now access and work with its files.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo apt install -y build-essential git autoconf libtool\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/jk34ophscssjnk2715knm/wolfcrypt2.png?rlkey=xez15e9xf0h8fo82agklbkgq2&st=2y3cqeyv&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs tools needed to build software: build-essential, git, autoconf, and libtool. The -y flag auto-confirms the installation.\"}, {\"command\": \"./autogen.sh\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/hs3xs51qqc6nfk6av90aa/wolfcrypt3.png?rlkey=wu4hve5rz74500fw8y6k3zd7v&st=pd577sdv&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command prepares the build configuration scripts for the project. It must be run before configuring and compiling the code.\"}, {\"command\": \"./configure --enable-tls13 --enable-opensslextra --enable-dilithium --enable-kyber\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/hvgawhztljw2r7ygnrfqe/wolfcrypt4.png?rlkey=hp1y5k101ky092fi3r3vfbxkg&st=nci4f69w&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command sets up the build to include TLS 1.3, OpenSSL extra features, and support for Dilithium and Kyber. It customizes what features will be built into wolfssl.\"}, {\"command\": \"make -j$(nproc)\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/6au335x0hzf7imppzcern/wolfcrypt5.png?rlkey=az69vi2kxz6fukiqva2pb24ki&st=o1g2ap3u&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the wolfssl project using all CPU cores. It speeds up the build process.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <stdlib.h>\\n#include <string.h>\\n#include <netdb.h>\\n#include <arpa/inet.h>\\n#include <unistd.h>\\n#include <wolfssl/options.h>\\n#include <wolfssl/ssl.h>\\n\\n#define SERVER \\\"google.com\\\"\\n#define PORT 443\\n\\nint main() {\\n    int ret;\\n    WOLFSSL_CTX* ctx = NULL;\\n    WOLFSSL* ssl = NULL;\\n    int sockfd = 0;\\n    struct sockaddr_in servAddr;\\n    struct hostent* host;\\n\\n    /* Initialize WolfSSL */\\n    wolfSSL_Init();\\n\\n    /* Enable debugging */\\n    wolfSSL_Debugging_ON();\\n\\n    /* Create and initialize WOLFSSL_CTX */\\n    if ((ctx = wolfSSL_CTX_new(wolfTLSv1_3_client_method())) == NULL) {\\n        fprintf(stderr, \\\"ERROR: failed to create WOLFSSL_CTX\\\\n\\\");\\n        return -1;\\n    }\\n\\n    /* Load CA certificates */\\n    const char* ca_cert = \\\"/etc/ssl/certs/ca-certificates.crt\\\";\\n    printf(\\\"Using CA certificates from: %s\\\\n\\\", ca_cert);\\n    if (wolfSSL_CTX_load_verify_locations(ctx, ca_cert, NULL) != SSL_SUCCESS) {\\n        fprintf(stderr, \\\"ERROR: failed to load CA certificates\\\\n\\\");\\n        wolfSSL_CTX_free(ctx);\\n        return -1;\\n    }\\n\\n    /* Verify peer */\\n    wolfSSL_CTX_set_verify(ctx, SSL_VERIFY_NONE, NULL);\\n\\n    /* Create a socket */\\n    if ((sockfd = socket(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, 0)) == -1) {\\n        perror(\\\"ERROR: failed to create socket\\\");\\n        wolfSSL_CTX_free(ctx);\\n        return -1;\\n    }\\n\\n    /* Resolve hostname */\\n    printf(\\\"Resolving hostname: %s\\\\n\\\", SERVER);\\n    if ((host = gethostbyname(SERVER)) == NULL) {\\n        herror(\\\"ERROR: failed to resolve hostname\\\");\\n        close(sockfd);\\n        wolfSSL_CTX_free(ctx);\\n        return -1;\\n    }\\n\\n    /* Set up server address */\\n    memset(&servAddr, 0, sizeof(servAddr));\\n    servAddr.sin_family = AF_INET;\\n    servAddr.sin_port = htons(PORT);\\n    memcpy(&servAddr.sin_addr, host->h_addr_list[0], host->h_length);\\n\\n    char ip_str[INET_ADDRSTRLEN];\\n    inet_ntop(AF_INET, &servAddr.sin_addr, ip_str, INET_ADDRSTRLEN);\\n    printf(\\\"Connecting to %s (%s) on port %d\\\\n\\\", SERVER, ip_str, PORT);\\n\\n    /* Connect to server */\\n    if (connect(sockfd, (struct sockaddr*)&servAddr, sizeof(servAddr)) != 0) {\\n        perror(\\\"ERROR: failed to connect to server\\\");\\n        close(sockfd);\\n        wolfSSL_CTX_free(ctx);\\n        return -1;\\n    }\\n    printf(\\\"TCP connection established successfully\\\\n\\\");\\n\\n    /* Create WOLFSSL object */\\n    if ((ssl = wolfSSL_new(ctx)) == NULL) {\\n        fprintf(stderr, \\\"ERROR: failed to create WOLFSSL object\\\\n\\\");\\n        close(sockfd);\\n        wolfSSL_CTX_free(ctx);\\n        return -1;\\n    }\\n\\n    /* Attach socket to WolfSSL */\\n    wolfSSL_set_fd(ssl, sockfd);\\n\\n    /* Perform SSL handshake */\\n    printf(\\\"Performing SSL handshake...\\\\n\\\");\\n    if ((ret = wolfSSL_connect(ssl)) != SSL_SUCCESS) {\\n        fprintf(stderr, \\\"ERROR: failed to connect (SSL), error: %d\\\\n\\\", wolfSSL_get_error(ssl, ret));\\n        wolfSSL_free(ssl);\\n        close(sockfd);\\n        wolfSSL_CTX_free(ctx);\\n        return -1;\\n    }\\n\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\nSuccessfully connected to %s:%d using %s\\\\n\\\", \\n           SERVER, PORT, wolfSSL_get_version(ssl));\\n    printf(\\\"Cipher suite: %s\\\\n\\\", wolfSSL_get_cipher(ssl));\\n\\n    /* Get server certificate */\\n    WOLFSSL_X509* cert = wolfSSL_get_peer_certificate(ssl);\\n    if (cert) {\\n        char* issuer = wolfSSL_X509_NAME_oneline(wolfSSL_X509_get_issuer_name(cert), 0, 0);\\n        char* subject = wolfSSL_X509_NAME_oneline(wolfSSL_X509_get_subject_name(cert), 0, 0);\\n        printf(\\\"Server certificate:\\\\n  Subject: %s\\\\n  Issuer: %s\\\\n\\\", subject, issuer);\\n        free(issuer);\\n        free(subject);\\n        wolfSSL_X509_free(cert);\\n    }\\n\\n    /* Shutdown SSL connection */\\n    printf(\\\"\\\\nClosing connection...\\\\n\\\");\\n    wolfSSL_shutdown(ssl);\\n    wolfSSL_free(ssl);\\n    close(sockfd);\\n    wolfSSL_CTX_free(ctx);\\n    wolfSSL_Cleanup();\\n\\n    printf(\\\"Connection closed successfully\\\\n\\\");\\n    return 0;\\n}\", \"explanation\": \"You can compile the program by using the command:\\ngcc -o wolfssl_example wolfssl_example.c -I.. -L../src/.libs -lwolfssl -lpthread.\\n\\nThis command builds the program named wolfssl_example using the source file wolfssl_example.c. It also links the WolfSSL library and pthread library needed for the program to work. After compiling, you should run the program to see the TLS handshake in action. Watching the handshake helps you understand how the secure connection is created between the client and server.\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/yg9vleo1rvg54h5y74wja/wolfssl_testing.png?rlkey=dn0bk91rh4r1ifldb0juhzlxs&st=q0e0gtsi&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"The image shows a successful TLS connection test using the WolfSSL library.  \\nIt establishes a secure connection to *google.com* using the TLSv1.3 protocol.  \\nThe output confirms that the handshake is completed and encryption is working properly.  \\nThis test demonstrates WolfSSL’s ability to handle secure communications efficiently.  \\nSuch testing is important for verifying security in embedded systems and network applications.\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-04-23 16:11:59','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(20,'cupqcmalkem-native','cuPQC mlkem-native','PQCP Initiative and NVIDIA','C,CUDA','1.0.0','11-12-2024','Apache License 2.0',1,NULL,0,'\"Kyber, Dilithium\"','cupqcmalkem-native is a specialized cryptographic library focused on implementing post-quantum key encapsulation algorithms, especially Kyber, and is designed for integration with Java applications via native code bindings. It targets researchers and developers interested in experimenting with or deploying NIST candidate post-quantum cryptography (PQC) algorithms in real-world systems. The library provides early access to quantum-resistant cryptographic mechanisms, enabling testing and benchmarking of PQC in Java environments, which are increasingly important as the threat of quantum computing grows.','The library’s specialization means it supports only a narrow set of algorithms, primarily Kyber, and does not offer the breadth of cryptographic primitives found in more general-purpose toolkits. The post-quantum cryptography field is still in flux, and algorithms may be subject to change, performance issues, or new vulnerabilities as standards evolve. The community around this library is limited, and documentation may not be as thorough as more established projects. Its focus on native integration may also introduce platform-specific challenges, and until PQC standards are finalized and adopted widely, its use in production systems carries significant risk regarding future compatibility and support.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(21,'gnupgfork','GnuPG Fork','Free Software Foundation Europe (FSFE), Werner Koch','C','2.4.8','14-05-2025','GNU General Public License',1,NULL,0,'\"Kyber, Dilithium, SPHINCS+, FrodoKEM\"','gnupgfork refers to a variant or fork of the primary GnuPG (GNU Privacy Guard) project, which itself is a highly respected open-source suite for email, file encryption, digital signatures, and public key management based on the OpenPGP standard. Forks of GnuPG are typically created to experiment with new features, adapt the tool for specific environments, or maintain backward compatibility with legacy systems. These forks usually retain the core design of GnuPG, offering strong encryption, a wide array of cryptographic algorithms, and integration with other open-source security tools.','The main limitation of a gnupgfork is the potential lag behind upstream GnuPG in critical security updates, bug fixes, and protocol improvements. Forks may not benefit from the rigorous peer review and community vetting that the main GnuPG project enjoys, possibly introducing security risks or stability issues. Additionally, documentation and support for forks are often less comprehensive, and compatibility with standard GnuPG features or third-party tools may be reduced or inconsistent.','[{\"command\": \"sudo apt install -y build-essential automake libtool gettext\", \"explanation\": \"awda\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo apt install -y pkg-config libusb-dev libudev-dev libreadline-dev\", \"explanation\": \"awda\"}, {\"command\": \"wget https://gnupg.org/ftp/gcrypt/npth/npth-1.6.tar.bz2\", \"explanation\": \"awda\"}, {\"command\": \"tar -xjf npth-1.6.tar.bz2\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"cd npth-1.6\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"./configure\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"cd ..\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"wget https://gnupg.org/ftp/gcrypt/libgpg-error/libgpg-error-1.47.tar.bz2\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"tar -xjf libgpg-error-1.47.tar.bz2\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"cd libgpg-error-1.47\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"./configure\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"cd ..\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"wget https://gnupg.org/ftp/gcrypt/libgcrypt/libgcrypt-1.10.3.tar.bz2\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"tar -xjf libgcrypt-1.10.3.tar.bz2\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"cd libgcrypt-1.10.3\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"./configure\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"cd ..\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"wget https://gnupg.org/ftp/gcrypt/libksba/libksba-1.6.6.tar.bz2\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"tar -xjf libksba-1.6.6.tar.bz2\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"cd libksba-1.6.6\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"./configure\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"cd ..\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"wget https://gnupg.org/ftp/gcrypt/libassuan/libassuan-2.5.6.tar.bz2\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"tar -xjf libassuan-2.5.6.tar.bz2\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"cd libassuan-2.5.6\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"./configure\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"cd ..\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"wget https://www.gnupg.org/ftp/gcrypt/gnupg/gnupg-2.4.8.tar.bz2\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"tar -xjf gnupg-2.4.8.tar.bz2\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"cd gnupg-2.4.8\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"mkdir build && cd build\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"../configure --enable-all-tests\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"make\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"make check\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"explanation\": \"test\"}]',NULL,NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(22,'gnutls','GnuTLS','GNU Project','C','3.8.9','07-02-2025','LGPL V2.1+',1,NULL,0,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','GnuTLS is a robust, open-source cryptographic library providing secure communications via implementations of SSL, TLS, and DTLS protocols. Targeted primarily at the GNU/Linux ecosystem, it offers support for a wide variety of cryptographic algorithms, X.509 and OpenPGP certificates, and is known for its modularity and extensive integration in free software stacks, including Linux distribution infrastructure and server applications. GnuTLS is designed to be easy to use for both developers and system administrators, with detailed documentation and a history of strong compliance with open standards.','GnuTLS, while feature-rich, is less widely adopted than OpenSSL, leading to a smaller user base, fewer third-party integrations, and less extensive real-world testing. Some advanced or highly specialized cryptographic extensions may be missing or less optimized, and updates to new protocol versions or cipher suites can lag behind competing libraries. For developers familiar with OpenSSL, the API and configuration model in GnuTLS may appear quite different, creating a learning curve and potential migration challenges.','[{\"command\": \"sudo apt install -y autopoint bison gperf gtk-doc-tools libtool nettle-dev libgmp-dev libunistring-dev libtasn1-6-dev libidn2-dev gettext pkg-config make automake autoconf build-essential git gawk libev-dev libunbound-dev p11-kit-dev libp11-kit-dev libtasn1-bin\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone https://gitlab.com/gnutls/gnutls.git\"}, {\"command\": \"cd gnutls\"}, {\"command\": \"./bootstrap\"}, {\"command\": \"./configure --prefix=/usr/local\"}, {\"command\": \"make -j$(nproc)\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\"}]',NULL,NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(23,'libjade','Libjade','PQClean Contributors and Various Researcher','C','1.0','02-05-2023','Public Domain and MIT',1,NULL,0,'\"Kyber, Dilithium, Falcon, SPHINCS+, NTRU, FrodoKEM\"','libjade is an open-source reference library for post-quantum cryptography, focusing on lattice-based schemes such as Kyber and Dilithium, which are leading candidates for NIST standardization. It aims to provide clean, portable, and auditable implementations of quantum-resistant algorithms, primarily for research, development, and cryptographic competitions.','libjade is not intended for production systems and may lack extensive documentation, robust testing, or side-channel resistance. As post-quantum research evolves, algorithms and interfaces may change, and the library’s focus on research means it is not as well supported or maintained as production-ready cryptographic toolkits.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(24,'libscapi','Libscapi','Bar-Ilan University','C++','3.0.1','30-11-2024','AGPLv3',1,NULL,0,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','libscapi is a cryptographic library tailored for secure computation and multi-party protocols, widely used in academic research for implementing advanced protocols such as secure multi-party computation (MPC), oblivious transfer, and zero-knowledge proofs. It offers a rich set of primitives and protocol implementations, enabling researchers to prototype, test, and benchmark privacy-preserving cryptographic schemes.','libscapi is not designed for general-purpose cryptography or production use; it has a steep learning curve, minimal focus on documentation and API stability, and may lack performance optimizations required in real-world deployments. The library is geared towards cryptography experts and researchers, making it unsuitable for most application developers.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(25,'libsignal','Libsignal','Open System Whispers (Signal Foundation)','Java, C, C++','5.40.0','23-02-2025','GPL-3.0',1,NULL,0,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','libsignal is the official implementation of the Signal Protocol, the cryptographic foundation for secure end-to-end messaging in applications like Signal, WhatsApp, and Facebook Messenger. It offers robust privacy through forward secrecy, deniable authentication, and strong encryption, and is widely regarded as the gold standard for secure messaging protocols.','libsignal is highly specialized and supports only the Signal Protocol for secure messaging, not general cryptographic primitives or protocols. Its integration can be complex and is best suited to messaging or real-time communication apps, not broader security needs.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(26,'mceleife-arm-m4','Mceleife-arm-m4','PQClean Project','C','2691B4915','29-11-2021','MIT',1,NULL,0,'\"Classic McEliece\"','mceleife-arm-m4 is a cryptographic library specifically optimized for the ARM Cortex-M4 processor, designed to provide efficient implementations of cryptographic algorithms in embedded and real-time systems. Its focus is on maximizing speed and minimizing resource consumption on this popular embedded microcontroller.','The specialization for ARM Cortex-M4 means this library is not portable to other architectures, and the algorithm selection may be limited by the microcontroller’s capabilities. Support, documentation, and community size are also typically smaller than with general-purpose cryptographic libraries.','[{\"command\": \"\", \"imageURL\": \"\", \"explanation\": \"\"}]','[{\"command\": \"\", \"explanation\": \"\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"\", \"explanation\": \"\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(27,'naci','NaCI\n','D.J. Bernstein, T.Lange,P.','C','2.1.0','06-08-2023','Public Domain',1,NULL,0,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','NaCl (Networking and Cryptography library) is a high-speed software library for network communication, public-key cryptography, and authenticated encryption. Its design emphasizes simplicity, security, and ease of use, providing APIs that minimize common cryptographic mistakes. NaCl has inspired several derivative projects, including libsodium.','NaCl does not include legacy or less secure algorithms, and its API choices may not fit all application requirements, especially where backward compatibility or custom protocol construction is needed.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(28,'openfhe','OpenFHE','Duality Technologies/OpenFHE Community','C++','1.2.4','02-05-2025','BSD 2-Clause',1,NULL,0,'\"BFV, CKKS, TFHE\"','OpenFHE is an open-source library for fully homomorphic encryption (FHE), enabling computations to be performed on encrypted data. It is used in privacy-preserving data analysis, secure cloud computation, and cryptography research, supporting multiple FHE schemes and parameter sets.','OpenFHE is resource-intensive and complex, with significant computational and memory overheads, making it unsuitable for most real-time or large-scale production applications at present. Its APIs and cryptosystem parameters are still evolving, and practical, efficient deployment remains a challenge.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(29,'oqsprovideropenssl','OQS Provider OpenSSL','Open Quantum Safe (OQS)','C,Python','0.8.0','15-03-2025','Apache 2.0, OpenSSL',1,NULL,0,'\"Kyber, Falcon, SPHINCS+, NTRU, FrodoKEM, NTS-KEM, NewHope, XMSS, McEliece(OpenSSL 3.0+)\"','oqsprovideropenssl is an OpenSSL provider that brings post-quantum cryptographic algorithms from the Open Quantum Safe (OQS) project to the widely used OpenSSL toolkit. It enables experimenting with quantum-resistant key exchange and signature algorithms alongside traditional cryptography.','The post-quantum algorithms are experimental, subject to ongoing research, and their security properties are not yet fully established. This provider is not recommended for production use, as future changes in standards or research may deprecate or break existing implementations.','[{\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/oqs-provider.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/q01gu5ncl4hd08zj56o0f/oqs0.png?rlkey=old759d12ykwylczsl3upajqw&st=5ziyars7&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the oqs-provider project from GitHub. It creates a folder with all the project files.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd oqs-provider\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/o88kyqhzq1evgiew74d72/oqs1.png?rlkey=l5eiwhg5r69rk21ewb5g6g2p7&st=k1a5i83t&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves you into the oqs-provider folder. You can now access and work with its files.\"}, {\"command\": \"mkdir build && cd build\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/dg882v523dawssnb87wws/oqs2.png?rlkey=e2azo81f7unsevdlygisq5p91&st=k05macco&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command creates a build folder and moves into it. It\'s used to keep the build files separate from the main source code.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo apt install libssl-dev\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/1hl383wpa6hl1x8y88nnm/oqs3.png?rlkey=550kovr50caqwapl4pkrad162&st=8b5xbj9g&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the development files for OpenSSL. These files are needed to build programs that use SSL/TLS.\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone --recursive https://github.com/open-quantum-safe/liboqs.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/8s2brliqwq5heso86c14l/oqs4.png?rlkey=n0qrponsbv1wqcek923bnawcy&st=8zcx7pj0&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the liboqs project and all its submodules. It creates a folder with the full project files. Ensure to clone the project inside the oqs-provider build directory if you want to follow the manual precisely or else if you have installed liboqs then you can skip to step 11.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd liboqs\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/55l8d0bruqptzekz9pwzk/oqs5.png?rlkey=lw9fdi18tuwwmpqvcu4kzc04b&st=xa18opfi&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves you into the liboqs folder. You can now work with its files.\"}, {\"command\": \"mkdir build && cd build\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/yg6h57a2z487yqa9v2h2h/oqs6.png?rlkey=espvf048b55smp409utqg086w&st=ds4li89l&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command creates a build folder and moves into it. It\'s where you will configure and build the project.\"}, {\"command\": \"cmake -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX=/opt/liboqs ..\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/ewwtthvj91p0j2c2grxjc/oqs7.png?rlkey=s5vmvrymai2tcugm3khi0j7y3&st=0tjcm4rj&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command sets up the build system and tells it to install the library to `/opt/liboqs`. It uses the source code from the folder above.\"}, {\"command\": \"make -j$(nproc)\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/lou7e10rp005f75flywzn/oqs8.png?rlkey=iz5bhbe0fwgrap0200tnkd29f&st=76kerthy&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the project using all available CPU cores. It speeds up the building process.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/l4ta77snev3eqmyt0p1fl/oqs9.png?rlkey=21gzae0pexxg1123nsgty1v5h&st=2n546quc&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the compiled `liboqs` library to `/opt/liboqs`. It uses `sudo` for permission to write to system folders.\"}, {\"command\": \"cmake -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release \\\\\\n  -DOPENSSL_ROOT_DIR=/usr \\\\\\n  -DOPENSSL_CRYPTO_LIBRARY=/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libcrypto.so \\\\\\n  -DOPENSSL_SSL_LIBRARY=/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libssl.so \\\\\\n  -DOPENSSL_INCLUDE_DIR=/usr/include \\\\\\n  -DCMAKE_PREFIX_PATH=$HOME/Desktop/oqs-provider/build/liboqs/build/liboqs-install ..\\n\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/p6v2c2xmgh2zmr9j98rli/oqs10.png?rlkey=lg42lta0fywga0bxx2qs5kisd&st=b960qrvm&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command sets up the `oqs-provider` build with OpenSSL paths and the location of the `liboqs` install. It prepares everything needed to compile the project correctly. If you have setup liboqs on another location you can change the PREFIX_PATH path location to the liboqs folder that you compile using make or cmake. Also run this command on oqs-provider build directory !\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"make -j$(nproc)\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/qhrz4zgfe5muvcbwj06of/oqs11.png?rlkey=o3lo2e0dgf5zkc0nbjqtsvmmy&st=32a30w1o&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the project using all available CPU cores. It speeds up the building process.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo make install\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/fq8emsf78qjvvp6tu2wed/oqs12.png?rlkey=1sgf4cyb25dfnblxben1p02lp&st=cj6bsta6&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs the built `oqs-provider` into your system. It uses `sudo` to allow writing to system directories.\"}]',NULL,NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(30,'pqcpmlkem-native','PQCP mlkem-native','PQCP Initiative','C','1.0.0-Beta','05-03-2025','Apache License 2.0',1,NULL,0,'\"Kyber, Dilithium\"','pqcpmlkem-native is a Java-native wrapper for post-quantum key encapsulation mechanisms (KEMs), allowing Java programs to test and incorporate quantum-resistant cryptography. It is mainly aimed at experimentation and research in the context of the upcoming transition to post-quantum standards.','The library is limited to a subset of KEM algorithms and is not intended for production deployment. As the post-quantum field is evolving, algorithms and APIs may change or become obsolete.','[{\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/pq-code-package/mlkem-native.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/hms665d50xnvr0j97vbqw/pqcp1.png?rlkey=zw29y0qfrhlhmxvlvvn6jlpda&st=jev3x9fv&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the `mlkem-native` project from GitHub to your computer. It creates a folder with the project files.\"}, {\"command\": \"make BACKEND=ref AUTO=0 OPT=0 -j4\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/e8atagkkebahjqonnzan2/pqcp2.png?rlkey=zav6lr78c9eq3e9eqz8r4eya5&st=uldb4tdb&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the mlkem-native project using the reference backend with no automatic tuning or optimization. It uses 4 CPU cores to speed up the build.Use this command if you\'re on a virtual machine or your CPU doesn’t support AVX instructions. It avoids crashes caused by test files using AVX2.\"}, {\"command\": \"make build\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/dkwwgye0f3yrb1x0cvut8/pqcp3.png?rlkey=bvccgnw6p8lrvrbxd92em7wai&st=fjzacxs2&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command compiles the project using the default build settings. It creates the necessary program files from the source code.\"}, {\"command\": \"make test\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/47cnzhme5sgqka979rs6g/pqcp4.png?rlkey=lzv3tmrkqfxgkykicsqwsgam1&st=kh7m5h83&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command runs the project\'s test files to check if everything works correctly. It helps make sure the build was successful.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"./test/build/mlkem512/bin/gen_KAT512\", \"explanation\": \"\"}]','[{\"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/lzu2puzqlbanrotfpsvtb/testing_mlkem-native.png?rlkey=9egtgd569st5bc1blx1tufdiv&st=h3ets2n8&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"\"}]','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(31,'pqcrypto-sidh','PQCrypto-SIDH','Microsoft Research','C','3.5.1','15-06-2022','MIT',1,NULL,0,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','pqcrypto-sidh is a library that implements the Supersingular Isogeny Diffie-Hellman (SIDH) protocol, which was once considered a promising candidate for post-quantum key exchange. It provides tools for experimenting with and evaluating SIDH-based cryptography.','SIDH has been broken by recent cryptanalysis and is no longer considered secure for new systems. The library should be used only for legacy research, not for any production or security-critical applications.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(32,'quantcrypt','QuantCrypt','ETH Zurich','Python, Rust','1.0.1','20-03-2025','MIT',1,NULL,0,'\"Kyber, Dilithium\"','QuantCrypt is a research-oriented cryptographic library focusing on quantum-safe schemes, allowing academic and experimental exploration of new algorithms resistant to quantum attacks. It is intended for cryptography researchers, students, and those evaluating emerging cryptographic ideas.','QuantCrypt is not production-ready, has limited documentation and support, and the algorithms it implements may change as research progresses. It is not intended or safe for use in real-world security applications.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(33,'skiffcrypto','Skiff Crypto','Skiff Technologies','TypeScript','1.0.3','14-06-2023','MIT',1,NULL,0,'\"PQC Unsupported\"','SkiffCrypto is a Rust-based cryptographic library developed for the Skiff email platform, with a focus on privacy and secure communication for end-to-end encrypted email and document collaboration. It provides modern cryptographic primitives tailored to Skiff’s use case.','SkiffCrypto is highly application-specific, not widely adopted outside Skiff, and lacks the general-purpose capabilities, documentation, and community support of major cryptographic libraries.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(34,'tink','tink','Google','C++','1.7.0','19-10-2023','Apache License 2.0',1,NULL,0,'\"Kyber, Dilithium, SPHINCS+\"','Tink is a cross-platform cryptographic library from Google, designed to make secure cryptography easier and safer for developers by providing simple, robust APIs for common use cases, such as encryption, digital signatures, and key management. It supports multiple programming languages and is widely used in production systems at Google and elsewhere.','Tink does not expose low-level cryptographic operations or allow custom algorithm integration, restricting its use for projects needing deep customization, experimental algorithms, or legacy protocol support.','[{\"command\": \"sudo apt install apt-transport-https curl gnupg zip unzip -y\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/58s948uznqfb8mivhzep4/tink0.png?rlkey=7yd8ox78ijptz8aj54ze1i5n1&st=etme54k6&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs tools needed for downloading and handling packages: apt-transport-https, curl, gnupg, zip, and unzip. The -y flag auto-approves the installation.\"}, {\"command\": \"curl -fsSL https://bazel.build/bazel-release.pub.gpg | gpg --dearmor > bazel.gpg\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/9q1jub4d0vz2lmlffl436/tink1.png?rlkey=zqveg2s5hgbbrkdnckjpfwzg3&st=qeszrhwq&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads Bazel’s GPG key and converts it to a format usable by your system. It helps verify Bazel packages during installation.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo mv bazel.gpg /etc/apt/trusted.gpg.d/\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/s7mz08vr5tinl7o654dnv/tink2.png?rlkey=fysj53gmv8r71wg6cmxlc02za&st=gbfzfakx&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves the Bazel GPG key to the system’s trusted key folder. It allows your system to trust Bazel package downloads.\"}, {\"command\": \"wget https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/releases/download/6.4.0/bazel-6.4.0-linux-x86_64\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/y1w80kv2ndepzxrdoxflo/tink3.png?rlkey=3ijffmaw36ql6l34et0m215t4&st=lwzeta5r&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads Bazel version 6.4.0 for Linux (64-bit) from GitHub. The file is saved in your current folder.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo mv bazel-6.4.0-linux-x86_64 /usr/local/bin/bazel\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/alg852li64sh9ths4ft02/tink4.png?rlkey=e4xh71nsptcgofu7eah481nxf&st=5lpl76n7&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves the downloaded Bazel file to /usr/local/bin/ and renames it to bazel. This makes it accessible from anywhere in the terminal.\"}, {\"command\": \"sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/bazel\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/zp6v862algzhdox894prf/tink5.png?rlkey=cg4279kut58aoauu39b5n8zfp&st=mjdfu6yk&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"ChatGPT said:\\nThis command gives the Bazel file permission to run as a program. It allows you to use bazel as a command.\"}, {\"command\": \"git clone https://github.com/tink-crypto/tink.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/1gw9cyphmic5kka4vtre7/tink6.png?rlkey=igrqgrf1fye9b0zsgn9s8gp2d&st=soly67x5&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the `tink` project from GitHub. It creates a folder with all the project files.\\n\"}, {\"command\": \"cd tink/cc\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/oppmq4ct7rtjycshs4s2c/tink7.png?rlkey=r1l5sps6e2qqtylj0afc08tdr&st=2htvi7ic&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command moves you into the cc folder inside the tink project. This folder contains the C++ version of Tink.\"}, {\"command\": \"bazel build ...\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/250c1m6urpmqozbj931c1/tink8.png?rlkey=ae73jd41xwotk7ukyk8c6bqya&st=a4o7yk5l&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command builds all targets in the Tink C++ project using Bazel. It compiles the full project and its dependencies.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"bazel test ...\", \"explanation\": \"awd\"}]',NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43'),(35,'tq42cryptography','TQ42 Cryptography','TU Darmstadt','Rust, C','0.2.1','2024-08-07','MIT',1,NULL,0,'\"Kyber, Dilithium, SPHINCS+\"','tq42cryptography is a lesser-known cryptographic library, with limited public documentation and adoption. It is intended for developers who need cryptographic operations in specific, possibly proprietary use cases.','Its security, reliability, and completeness are uncertain due to minimal peer review, small community, and lack of public success stories or professional audits. It should be used with caution, if at all, and not for critical applications.','[{\"command\": \"git clone --recursive https://github.com/terra-quantum-public/tq42-pqc-oss.git\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/897dbybt2k7les0pochlf/1.png?rlkey=o50s3wls9pwhetms310aj2kl2&st=xu3diho5&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command downloads the project from the GitHub link to your computer. The `--recursive` part also downloads any extra sub-projects (submodules) included in it.\"}, {\"command\": \"cd tq42-pqc-oss\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/z6xqvrtyhvvwzdhobqeoz/2.png?rlkey=ry0cmocrizvtpkv8jn0dsbzy3&st=s60w0mj1&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command changes your current folder to `tq42-pqc-oss`. It lets you work with the files inside that folder.\"}, {\"command\": \"mkdir build && cd build\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/77tu1dqquy8lxzahjsfbf/3.png?rlkey=gfv1xj9w04iqde2sjl44n9k8r&st=rbbat7u6&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command creates a new folder named `build` and then moves into it. It’s usually used to keep build files separate from the main source code.\"}, {\"command\": \"python3 -m venv venv\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/o4lbraa80jq0h44vt8nv1/4.png?rlkey=dpiupqmjhryhic6lkd9lmelet&st=3t77n2tv&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command creates a virtual environment named venv using Python 3. It helps keep project dependencies separate from other projects or system packages.\"}, {\"command\": \"source venv/bin/activate\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/hlu48rucvq1fyvitk48fx/5.png?rlkey=ksab24hwy1abbdlhjc94lzn2k&st=92o9f22s&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command activates the virtual environment you created. After this, any Python packages you install will only affect this project.\"}, {\"command\": \"pip install pytest\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/qteieszuj7ryfs4wl5ll8/6.png?rlkey=1d2uukxmy4ppdmpudvcn42a49&st=6e0k0eqr&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command installs pytest, a tool used to run and manage tests in Python. It helps check if your code works correctly.\"}, {\"command\": \"cmake ..\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/dol141i2553zgorp0ss8o/7.png?rlkey=ezym5h1cxxqov0l238ft8ekfd&st=p333vncu&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"ChatGPT said:\\nThis command runs CMake to set up the build files using the source code from the folder above (..). It prepares everything needed to compile the project.\"}, {\"command\": \"cmake --build .\", \"imageURL\": \"https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/qw2a5i44tft5k5jmzpdvi/8.png?rlkey=ke61mjtg76ozdpymkc7z4tbqb&st=tyqmvxzm&raw=1\", \"explanation\": \"This command builds (compiles) the project using the files prepared by CMake. It creates the final program or library from the source code.\"}]','[{\"command\": \"cd build/test\", \"explanation\": \"awda\"}, {\"command\": \"./LibPQTest\", \"explanation\": \"awdaw\"}]',NULL,'2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43','2026-05-06 19:57:43');
